DEFINITION: Car sales, multiplier by type
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on car sales by country/region and car type.  A value of 1.0 leaves car sales unchanged.  An increase over time to 2.0 would approximately double car sales of the specified type relative to the base case (total car sales will be normalized and therefore unchanged relative to the base case).

NAME: CARS (Large)
SCENARIO NAME: Carbon (atmospheric) absorbed yearly by oceans and non-forest land sources
DEFINITION: Carbon (atmospheric) absorbed yearly by oceans and non-forest land sources
Parameter Explanation: Rate of carbon absorption - this parameter defines the amoung of atmospheric carbon (expressed in billion tons) that oceans or other sinks (except forests) absorb each year. Although this value should ultimately be a function of the carbon in the atmosphere and the carbon in the sinks of the ocean, land, and biological systems (and hence a computed variable), it is common in atmospheric models to specify it as a single, constant parameter.

DEFINITION: Cultural region shift on survival/self-expression
Parameter Explanation: Cultural shift on the survival/self-expression index.  It is an additive factor that represents the average "shift" in the index for survival/self-expression for a given cultural region (relative to what would be expected based of level of GDP per capita), as identified in the World Value Survey project.  The initial value is determined from data, but the user could change the value over time to represent cultural convergence or divergence.

DEFINITION: Energy demand to GDP ratio, annual technology-based change
Parameter Explanation: Annual percentage change in energy demand as a result of technological change.  This parameter helps represent the historic phenomenon of considerable decrease over time in energy requirements per unit of economic output ("dematerialization").  It is an uncertain but very important parameter.  A value of -1 would represent an annual efficiency improvement of 1 percent.

DEFINITION: Livestock herd productivity gain with grain feeding

SCENARIO NAME: Resources of fossil fuels, ultimate, BBL
DEFINITION: Resources of fossil fuels, ultimate,
Parameter Explanation: Resources of fossil fuels, ultimate, billion barrels of oil equivalent.  This value only sets an initial condition; thereafter resources are computed taking into account depletion from production.

NAME: QE (Wind)
SCENARIO NAME: Elasticity of industrial (incl energy) use of crops with energy price
DEFINITION: Elasticity of industrial (incl energy) use of crops with energy price
Parameter Explanation: Elasticity of industrial (incl energy) use of crops with energy price.  0 turns it off.

NAME: QEUNCON
SCENARIO NAME: Q (capital costs-to-output ratio), unconventional, currency/barrel
DEFINITION: Q (capital costs-to-output ratio), unconventional
Parameter Explanation: Capital output ratio for unconventional energy, in dollars, per barrel of production capacity, by region and energy category.  This variable determines how many dollars of capital are required in the production of a barrel of oil equivalent in each energy category.  It therefore represents the cost of energy production.  QEUNCON is exogenous only for nuclear and renewable energy.  Values for oil, gas, and coal are computed endogenously (and depend on remaining resources) and should be examined only as indicators.  To change the cost pattern for those energy forms, use resorm and increase or decrease resources.  Values for renewable and nuclear energy can be exogenously changed, but you should maintain the initial value of the base case.  A series of gradually lower costs could represent technological progress (e.g. in the solar component of renewable).  A series of gradually higher costs could represent the impact of environmental factors (e.g. increasing costs of nuclear waste disposal).  Higher or lower values will increase or decrease investment in a particular energy category and will affect its production level.  You should be aware that investment will respond only to changes over time in QE and not to changes in the initial condition.

NAME: VADD (ICTech)
SCENARIO NAME: Energy production technology, annual decease in cost
DEFINITION: Energy production technology, annual decease in cost
DISPLAY UNITS: Annual Decrease in Energy Production Cost
Parameter Explanation: Energy technology advance rate (decrease in cost of energy production), expressed in decimal form (e.g. 0.01 equals 1 percent annual growth, by energy type).  Use, for example, to decrease the cost of renewable energy over time.  A value of 0.01 applied to renewable energy would force an annual decrease in the costs of producing solar energy of 1% each year, representing continued technological advance in such production (a value of -0.01 would represent a negative cost decrease, that is, a cost increase).

NAME: XS (Energy)
SCENARIO NAME: Energy price override
DEFINITION: Exogenous energy price when set above 0.0
Parameter Explanation: Energy price in dollars per barrel of oil equivalent, by region.  Energy price (ENPRI) is normally computed endogenously so as to balance supply and demand of energy.  If you set enprix to positive, nonzero values, you can override the endogenous computation with your own price level.  It is possible to intervene with energy prices only for select years by leaving enprix at zero for other years and specifying enprix only for selected ones.  You might do this, for instance, to represent a period in which government controls energy prices domestically or a cartel sets them internationally.

NAME: actreaon
SCENARIO NAME: Action/Reaction Switch (1=On, 0=Off)
DEFINITION: Action/Reaction Switch (1=On, 0=Off)
Parameter Explanation: Action-reaction switch.  A value of 1 (as in the base case) turns on an action-reaction dynamic in the determination of threat.  A value of 0 turns it off.

NAME: agconv
SCENARIO NAME: Agricultural demand convergence time to function
DEFINITION: Agricultural demand convergence time to function
Parameter Explanation: Agriculture demand convergence time, represents the time required  for agricultural demand to converge to the function's predicted values, in years. Initial country data may deviate from cross-sectional predictions due to possible data errors or unique country factors. This parameter assumes that over time, such discrepancies will align with the predicted values. A high value like 10000 stops convergence; a low value like 10 speeds it up.

NAME: ageofmarriagem
SCENARIO NAME: Age of Marriage, Value, multiplier
DEFINITION: Age of Marriage Value, multiplier
Parameter Explanation: The rate of change for age of marriage impacted by a multliplier.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: ageofmarriagetfrelas
DISPLAY NAME: Elasticity of Age of Marriage to Total Fertility Rate
SCENARIO NAME: Elasticity of age of marriage to total fertility rate
DEFINITION: Elasticity of age of marriage to total fertility rate
Parameter Explanation: Responsiveness of TFR to changes in average age of marriage from expected value, i.e., base case forecast. A value of .01 will decrease TFR by .01 when age of marriage is one year more than the base case forecast.

NAME: aginvm
SCENARIO NAME: Agricultural investment multiplier
DEFINITION: Agricultural investment multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on agriculture investment, by region and without units. A value of 1 indicates no change. Values greater than 1 increase investment proportionally, and values less than 1 decrease it. Avoid changing the initial year value; instead, adjust the multiplier over time.

NAME: aglossprodm
DISPLAY NAME: Loss rate at point of agricultural production, multiplier
SCENARIO NAME: Loss rate of agricultural production
DEFINITION: Loss rate of agricultural production
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on agricultural production losses adjusts the proportion of food production lost at the point of production (for example, to pests in the field.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: agon
SCENARIO NAME: Agriculture-economy linkage parameter (1=On, 0=Off)
DEFINITION: Agriculture-economy linkage parameter (1=On, 0=Off)
Parameter Explanation: Agriculture switch turns on or off the linkages  between the agricultural submodel and all others, including economy. A value of 1 turns the linkages on; 0 turns them off. Useful for isolating submodels during analysis. Typically set to 1.

NAME: agstkadjsw
SCENARIO NAME: Switch to turn off adjustment of agriculture stocks (if =1)
DEFINITION: Switch to turn off adjustment of agriculture stocks (if =1)
Parameter Explanation: Agricultural stock change switch eliminates the impact of supply and demand imbalances on agricultural food stocks.  A value of 1 turns on the switch for highly specialized scenarios.

NAME: agtrdadjsw
SCENARIO NAME: Switch to turn off adjustment of agriculture trade to stocks (if =1)
DEFINITION: Switch to turn off adjustment of agriculture trade to stocks (if =1)
Parameter Explanation: Agricultural trade switch eliminates the impact of domestic and international food stocks changes on trade ratios. A value of 1 turns on the switch for highly specialized scenarios.

NAME: aiddon
SCENARIO NAME: Aid (foreign) donations as % of GDP
DEFINITION: Aid (foreign) donations as % of GDP
Parameter Explanation: Aid (foreign) donations as % of GDP.  A coefficient of foreign assistance, by country/region.  It is in percentage form and is the percentage of GDP given in foreign aid (e.g., -0.2 equals 0.2 percent of GDP).

NAME: aidgradpoint
SCENARIO NAME: Aid (foreign), income per capita that no longer qualifies countries for aid
DEFINITION: Aid (foreign), income per capita that no longer qualifies countries for aid
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on aid received..  The model will allocate available aid so that all recipients receive aid proportional to specified targets, not necessarily equal to those targets.

NAME: aidlp
SCENARIO NAME: Aid (foreign), loan portion
DEFINITION: Aid (foreign) loan portion

NAME: aidrecadd
DISPLAY NAME: Aid (foreign) receipts additive factor (Percentage of GDP)
SCENARIO NAME: Aid (foreign) receipts additive factor (Percentage of GDP)
DEFINITION: Aid (foreign) receipts additive factor (Percentage of GDP)
Parameter Explanation: Additive factor on aid received.  The model will allocate available aid so that all recipients receive aid proportional to specified targets, not necessarily equal to those targets.

NAME: aidrecgovconp
SCENARIO NAME: Aid (foreign) receipts, portion going to government consumption
DEFINITION: Aid (foreign) receipts, portion going to government consumption
Parameter Explanation: Aid, share of aid received that is disbursed towards government consumption spending (the rest is used as transfer).

NAME: aidrecm
SCENARIO NAME: Aid (foreign) receipts multiplier
DEFINITION: Aid (foreign) receipts multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on aid received..  The model will allocate available aid so that all recipients receive aid proportional to specified targets, not necessarily equal to those targets.

NAME: aidsdratem
SCENARIO NAME: AIDS death rate as % of HIV infection rate, multiplier
DEFINITION: AIDS death rate as percent of HIV infection rate, multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on AIDS death rate as a percentage of HIV infection rate. It refers to the percentage of infected individuals in a population who die in a given year, not to the percentage who ultimately die of AIDS.

NAME: aidsdrtadvr
SCENARIO NAME: AIDS death rate, technical annual advance rate in control
DEFINITION: AIDS death rate, technical annual advance rate in control
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the technical advance rate in control of deaths from those with AIDS. For example, anti-viral therapies.

NAME: aimachiqm
SCENARIO NAME: Artificial Intelligence Machine IQ multiplier
DEFINITION: Artificial Intelligence Machine IQ multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on Artificial Inteligence Machine IQ.

NAME: ally
SCENARIO NAME: Alliance membership (0=none; 1=yalliance)
DEFINITION: Alliance membership (0=none; 1=alliance)
Parameter Explanation: Alliance membership switch.  A value of 1 indicates membership in the acting alliance and a value of 2 indicates membership in the reacting alliance (either alliance can consist of a single country or region).  Alliances can form or dissolve over time; membership in alliances can change.  None of that will, however, happen endogenously; you must specify alliance structures.  Alliance membership only affects war damage, not threat levels or war outbreak.

NAME: aquaculconv
SCENARIO NAME: Aquacultture convergence time
DEFINITION: Aquacultture convergence time
Parameter Explanation: Aquaculture growth rate convergence time represents the time for  aquaculture growth rates to converge to zero, in years.

NAME: aquaculgr
SCENARIO NAME: Aquaculture growth rate, initial
DEFINITION: Aquaculture growth rate, initial
Parameter Explanation: Initial annual growth rate for aquaculture production (freshwater or marine) by region, expressed as a percentage. Avoid changing after the initial year; use a multiplier instead.

NAME: aquaculm
SCENARIO NAME: Aquaculture multiplier
DEFINITION: Aquaculture multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on aquaculture production, without units, by region. A value of 1 indicates no change; higher values increase demand, and lower values decrease it. Maintain the initial year's value, gradually adjusting the multiplier thereafter.

NAME: armsimmaxpctmilexp
DISPLAY NAME: Share of GDS(MIL) cap on MARMS; 0.5 means 50% of GDS(MIL) can be spent on arms
SCENARIO NAME: Share of GDS(MIL) cap on MARMS; 0.5 means 50% of GDS(MIL) can be spent on arms
DEFINITION: Share of GDS(MIL) cap on MARMS; 0.5 means 50% of GDS(MIL) can be spent on arms
Parameter Explanation: Share of GDS(MIL) cap on MARMS

NAME: bilateralsw
SCENARIO NAME: Bilateral Switch
DEFINITION: Bilateral Switch
Parameter Explanation: Switch to compute bilateral variables.

NAME: bilateraltradeforwardlinksw
SCENARIO NAME: Bilateral Trade Forward Linkage Switch
DEFINITION: Bilateral Trade Forward Linkage Switch
Parameter Explanation: Switch to compute forward linkages from bilateral trade.

NAME: birthmshr
SCENARIO NAME: Births, male share
DEFINITION: Births, male share
Parameter Explanation: Births, male share.  Slightly more than 50% of births are males and more males die at most ages than do females.  This is an empirical value and you would normally not want to change it.

NAME: calmax
SCENARIO NAME: Calories, maximum needed per day per person
DEFINITION: Calories, maximum needed per day per person
Parameter Explanation: Maximum kilocalories needed per person per day. This biologically determined value should generally not change over time.

NAME: calmeatm
SCENARIO NAME: Calories, portion obtained from meat, maximum (first year only)
DEFINITION: Calories, portion obtained from meat multiplier (first year only)
Parameter Explanation: Maximum proportion of calories from meat, increasing with income up to this cap. The value, between 0 and 1, is typically set only in the first year.

NAME: carabr
SCENARIO NAME: Carbon (atmospheric) absorbed yearly by oceans and non-forest land sources
DEFINITION: Carbon (atmospheric) absorbed yearly by oceans and non-forest land sources
Parameter Explanation: Rate of carbon absorption - this parameter defines the amoung of atmospheric carbon (expressed in billion tons) that oceans or other sinks (except forests) absorb each year. Although this value should ultimately be a function of the carbon in the atmosphere and the carbon in the sinks of the ocean, land, and biological systems (and hence a computed variable), it is common in atmospheric models to specify it as a single, constant parameter.

NAME: carannwi
SCENARIO NAME: Net emissions from fossil fuels, initial
DEFINITION: Net emissions from fossil fuels, initial
Parameter Explanation: This parameter sets the initial net emissions from fossil fuels.

NAME: carbtax
SCENARIO NAME: Carbon tax
DEFINITION: Carbon tax
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that sets the carbon tax, expressed in dollars/ton of carbon generated and affects (increases) energy prices and (decreases) demand. Values will normally be above 50 and as an example, a value of 100 ($100/ton) will add about $0.20 to the price of a gallon of gas.

NAME: carforst
SCENARIO NAME: Carbon sequestered by forests
DEFINITION: Carbon sequestered by forests, gigatons per million hectaresx
Parameter Explanation: Carbon generated by deforestation - this parameter specifies the amount of atmospheric carbon (expressed in billion tons) that will be added by deforestation (expressed in billion hectares of land). Normally you would not change this parameter over time, because it should be a fairly fixed parameter.

NAME: carfuel1
SCENARIO NAME: Carbon generated by burning oil
DEFINITION: Carbon generated by burning oil
DISPLAY UNITS: Billion Tons per Barrel Oil Equivalent
Parameter Explanation: Carbon generated by burning oil, expressed in billion tons per billion barrels of oil equivalent.  Although this is an empirical value, it is possible that some advance technologies might sequester rather than release carbon into the atmosphere.

NAME: carfuel2
SCENARIO NAME: Carbon generated by burning natural gas
DEFINITION: Carbon generated by burning natural gas
DISPLAY UNITS: Billion Tons per Barrel Oil Equivalent
Parameter Explanation: Carbon generated by burning natural gas expressed in billion tons per billion barrels of oil equivalent .  Although this is an empirical value, it is possible that some advance technologies might sequester rather than release carbon into the atmosphere.

NAME: carfuel3
SCENARIO NAME: Carbon generated by burning coal
DEFINITION: Carbon generated by burning coal
DISPLAY UNITS: Billion Tons per Barrel Oil Equivalent
Parameter Explanation: Carbon generated by burning coal expressed in billion tons per billion barrels of oil equivalent.  Although this is an empirical value, it is possible that some advance technologies might sequester rather than release carbon into the atmosphere.

NAME: carinit
SCENARIO NAME: Carbon dioxide in atmosphere, base year
DEFINITION: Carbon dioxide in atmosphere, base year
Parameter Explanation: Initial level of carbon dioxide in atmosphere in the base year, expressed in billion tons. The value in the model should be relatively accurate.

NAME: carprein
SCENARIO NAME: Carbon dioxide in atmosphere, pre-industrial
DEFINITION: Carbon dioxide in atmosphere, pre-industrial
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that defines the pre-industrial atmospheric carbon levels, expressed in billion tons. Normally, a user will not change this parameter over time.

NAME: carsconv
SCENARIO NAME: Car sales, convergence time to functions
DEFINITION: Car sales, convergence time to functions
Parameter Explanation: Convergence time for car sales in years. This value determines the number of years over which all countries/regions will converge to the chosen function (as determined by the switch, vehfuncsw) for the computation of car sales per year.  A value of 10000 would effectively turn off convergence, so that initial country-specific variations from the function would be maintained over time.  A value of 60 would lead to near convergence by the middle of the 21st century.  Very rapid convergence seems improbable in the face of fundamental country differences in infrastructure, land area, culture, etc.

NAME: carstotm
SCENARIO NAME: Car sales, total multiplier
DEFINITION: Car sales, total multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on total car sales by country/region.  A value of 1.0 leaves total sales unchanged.  An increase over time to 2.0 would approximately double total sales relative to the base case (sales by type will not always change proportionately, because of differing relationships with total sales).

NAME: cconstsw
DISPLAY NAME: Consumption Constant Switch (1 is on, 0 is off)
SCENARIO NAME: Consumption Constant Switch (1 is on, 0 is off)
DEFINITION: Consumption Constant Switch (1 is on, 0 is off)
Parameter Explanation: Consumption constant switch, with 1 indicating on and 0 indicating off.

NAME: cdmf
SCENARIO NAME: Civilian damage that war does to economy/population
DEFINITION: Civilian damage factor in war; portion of economy
Parameter Explanation: Civilian damage factor.  This reactivity parameter links the severity of conventional war and the power of the opposing alliance to civilian damage (both population killed and economic capital destroyed).  A value of 0 will uncouple conventional war from damage and a value of 1 will make damage proportional to the war severity and opposing power.  There is no comparable parameter for the impact of nuclear war on civilians because the model always assumes civilian damage; in fact, it extends some such damage beyond the regions involved in nuclear war to third party countries (from fall-out and other collateral damage).

NAME: cexovals
SCENARIO NAME: Consumption Exogenous Values (-100 is off)
DEFINITION: Consumption Exogenous Values (-100 is off)
Parameter Explanation: Consumption exogenous values is used to set consumption values exogenously, with a value of -100 to turn the setting off.

NAME: climeconimplin
DISPLAY NAME: Climate change to economy impact, linear term coefficient
SCENARIO NAME: Climate change to economy impact, linear term coefficient
DEFINITION: Climate change to economy impact, linear term coefficient
Parameter Explanation: Parameteter on linear term in the quadratic function that links changes in temperature to impact on economy in percentage terms.

NAME: climeconimpperctrysw
DISPLAY NAME: Climate chnge to econ impact using country specific temp (1 is on)
SCENARIO NAME: Climate chnge to econ impact using country specific temp (1 is on)
DEFINITION: Climate chnge to econ impact using country specific temp (1 is on)
Parameter Explanation: Switch to activate climate change impact on economu using country-specific temperatures, as opposed to using global temperature. A value of 1 indicates it is on, and 0 indicates off.

NAME: climeconimpsq
DISPLAY NAME: Climate chnge to econ impact, sq term coef (Nordhaus 0.236;Stern 2.22)
SCENARIO NAME: Climate chnge to econ impact, sq term coef (Nordhaus 0.236;Stern 2.22)
DEFINITION: Climate change to economy impact, squared term coefficient
Parameter Explanation: Parameteter on squared term in the quadratic function that links changes in temperature to impact on economy in percentage terms.

NAME: climeconimpstk
DISPLAY NAME: Climate chnge to econ impact, portion affecting production stocks
SCENARIO NAME: Climate chnge to econ impact, portion affecting production stocks
DEFINITION: Climate chnge to econ impact, portion affecting  productivity or capital stocks
Parameter Explanation: This parameter determines the share of production function (technology and/or climate stock) that climate change to economic impact variable eliminates. For example, CLIMECONIMP of 2 percent times 0.5 will indicate a 1 percent reduction of stock in capital/technology.

NAME: climeconimpsw
DISPLAY NAME: Climate change to economy impact switch (1=on)
SCENARIO NAME: Climate change to economy impact switch (1=on)
DEFINITION: Climate change to economy impact switch (1=on)
Parameter Explanation: Switch to turn on the impacts of temperature rise on non-agricultural sectors.

NAME: clnf
SCENARIO NAME: Calorie needs adjustment, for age distribution
DEFINITION: Calorie needs adjustment, for age distribution
Parameter Explanation: Calorie need factor or multiplier on calorie needs, by region. Usually set at 1. It adjusts regional calorie requirements to address food shortages impacting infant mortality. A value of 0 turns off the feedback between food shortages and infant mortality for a region.

NAME: clpccvm
SCENARIO NAME: Calories per Capita, Coefficient of Variation (Std. Dev/Mean) multiplier
DEFINITION: Calories per Capita, Coefficient of Variation (Std. Dev/Mean) multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on coefficient of variation (Std. Dev/Mean) for calories per capita.

NAME: clpcmderm
SCENARIO NAME: Calories per Capita, Minimum Dietary Energy Requirement multiplier
DEFINITION: Calories per Capita, Minimum Dietary Energy Requirement multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier for the Calories per Capita Minimum Dietary Energy Requirement.

NAME: clsexp
SCENARIO NAME: Calorie shortage link to starvation, exponent (higher value lowers starvation)
DEFINITION: Calorie shortage link to starvation, exponent (higher value lowers starvation)
Parameter Explanation: Exponent parameter that links calorie shortage to starvation. Higher values lower starvation and lower values increase starvation.

NAME: co2perm
SCENARIO NAME: Atmospheric percentage of CO2 multiplier
DEFINITION: Atmospheric percentage of CO2 multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on atmospheric percentage of CO2.

NAME: co2prein
SCENARIO NAME: CO2, parts per million in atmosphere, pre-industrial base
DEFINITION: CO2, parts per million in atmosphere, pre-industrial base
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that defines the pre-industrial level of atmospheric CO2 in parts per million. Normally, a user would not change this parameter over time. See also carprein - that sets the pre-industrial atmospheric carbon levels in billion tons.

NAME: confforsw
SCENARIO NAME: Conflict forward linkage switch (1=On, 0=Off)
DEFINITION: Conflict forward linkage switch (1=On, 0=Off)
Parameter Explanation: Switch that links the forward linkage of conflict with multifactory productivity/democracy. A value of 0 (base case) turns off the impact of intrastate conflict/state failure/fragility on multifactor productivity or democracy while a value of 1 turn it on.

NAME: contiguity
SCENARIO NAME: Contiguity (geographic proximity) of countries/regions
DEFINITION: Contiguity (geographic proximity) of countries/regions
Parameter Explanation: The physical distance between two countries/reigons.  The scale is:  1=land contiguity; 2=0=12 miles; 3=12-24 miles; 4=24-150 miles; 5=150-400 miles; 6=more than 400 miles.  Normally you would not change this value over time.

NAME: contrusm
SCENARIO NAME: Contraception use multiplier
DEFINITION: Contraception use multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Contraception use multiplier.  A multiplier on contraception use, by region.  It normally has a value of 1.  Higher values increase contraception use and lower values decrease it.

NAME: cookstovesadd
DISPLAY NAME: Cook Stoves Net added (this year only)
SCENARIO NAME: Cook Stoves Net added (this year only)
DEFINITION: Cook Stoves Net added (this year only)

NAME: cpctnduse
SCENARIO NAME: Percent used of needed consumption
DEFINITION: Percent used of needed consumption
Parameter Explanation: Proportion of required consumption that is allocated to address the impact of aging.

NAME: cpowdf
SCENARIO NAME: Conventional power, damage done by war
DEFINITION: Conventional power, damage done by war
Parameter Explanation: Conventional power damage factor.  This reactivity parameter links the severity of conventional war and the power of the opposing alliance to the losses of conventional power (personnel and equipment).  A value of 0 will uncouple conventional war from damage and a value of 1 will make damage proportional to the war severity and power of the opponents.

NAME: cpowf
SCENARIO NAME: Conventional power, factor controlling conversion of military spending
DEFINITION: Conventional power, factor controlling conversion of military spending

NAME: cultshmp
SCENARIO NAME: Cultural region shift on materialism/postmaterialism
DEFINITION: Cultural region shift on materialism/postmaterialism
Parameter Explanation: Cultural shift on the materialism/post-materialism index.  It is an additive factor that represents the average "shift" in the index for materialism/post-materialism for a given cultural region (relative to what would be expected based of level of GDP per capita), as identified in the World Value Survey project.  The initial value is determined from data, but the user could change the value over time to represent cultural convergence or divergence.

NAME: cultshse
SCENARIO NAME: Cultural region shift on survival/self-expression
DEFINITION: Cultural region shift on survival/self-expression
Parameter Explanation: Cultural shift on the survival/self-expression index.  It is an additive factor that represents the average "shift" in the index for survival/self-expression for a given cultural region (relative to what would be expected based of level of GDP per capita), as identified in the World Value Survey project.  The initial value is determined from data, but the user could change the value over time to represent cultural convergence or divergence.

NAME: cultshts
SCENARIO NAME: Cultural region shift on traditional/secular-rational
DEFINITION: Cultural region shift on traditional/secular-rational
Parameter Explanation: Cultural shift on the traditional/rational-secular index.  It is an additive factor that represents the average "shift" in the index for traditional/rational-secular for a given cultural region (relative to what would be expected based of level of GDP per capita), as identified in the World Value Survey project.  The initial value is determined from data, but the user could change the value over time to represent cultural convergence or divergence.

NAME: cwarbase
SCENARIO NAME: Conventional war, base probability in percentage terms
DEFINITION: Conventional war, base probability (percentage terms, 0-100)
Parameter Explanation: Conventional warfare base probability - the model adds or substracts from this value incremental probabilities of war that depend on many factors (power balances, democracy levels, etc.).  Specify values between 0 and 1 for the base annual probability of war between any actor and target.  Normally the values should be quite near 0 and in the base case all values are set to zero.

NAME: cwarf
SCENARIO NAME: Conventional war switch (>100=on, if WarOn=1)
DEFINITION: Conventional war switch (>100=on, if WarOn = 1)
Parameter Explanation: Conventional war factor.  If WarOn = 1, by setting the value of this parameter equal to 100 or more you can force the model to generate a wide-spread war. Use of this parameter is only recommended for testing the functioning of war in the model; it has no policy interpretation.

NAME: cwarsv
SCENARIO NAME: Conventional war severity; portion of weaponry used
DEFINITION: Conventional war severity; portion of weaponry used
Parameter Explanation: Conventional war severity factor.  This coefficient determines what portion of the conventional armament potential will be used when a war erupts.  Values should range from 0 (none) to 1 (all).

NAME: deathtrpvm
SCENARIO NAME: Deaths from traffic per vehicle multiplier
DEFINITION: Deaths from traffic per vehicle multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on deaths from traffic accidents per vehicle. A value of 1 leaves values unchanged, while a value of 2 would double death per vehicle relatibe to the base case.

NAME: deathtrpvsetar
DISPLAY NAME: Deaths fr traffic p/ vehicle Standard Error Target
SCENARIO NAME: Deaths from traffic per vehicle Standard Error Target
DEFINITION: Number of Standard Errors to Target for Deaths from traffic per vehicle
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the target standard errors for DEATHTRPV forecast. Value range between -2 to 2, with 0 indicating that the target is turned off. Used in combination with deathtrpvseyrtar.

NAME: deathtrpvseyrtar
DISPLAY NAME: Years to Target Traffic Deaths p/veh Std Error
SCENARIO NAME: Years to Target Deaths from traffic per vehicle Standard Error
DEFINITION: Years to Target number of Standard Errors for Deaths from traffic per vehicle
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies that number of years to reach the standard error target for DEATHTRPV.

NAME: democconv
SCENARIO NAME: Democracy, convergence time to expected value
DEFINITION: Democracy, convergence time to expected value
Parameter Explanation: This parameter specifies the convergence time of political variables (DEMOC) to predicted value. Very often initial data values for countries will differ from values predicted by a cross-sectional relationship.  It is never certain whether such differences involve data errors or factors idiosyncratic to countries.  A paradigmatic assumption of IFs is that, over time, values for such variables will often gradually converge to the values predicted by the function and the initial country-specific "shift" should disappear. A high value such as 10000 will effectively turn off the convergence process altogether, while a low value such as 10 will make it very rapid.

NAME: democimpoth
SCENARIO NAME: Democracy impetus from non-specific forces, 0 is neutral; Polity scale
DEFINITION: Democracy impetus from non-specific forces, 1-10 (10=most); Polity scale
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that determines the democracy impetus from non-specific forces such as the spread of a systemic value around democracy. The scale ranges from 1-10 (10=most) and is based on the Polity scale.  Normally interventions with the parameter would be variable over time (e.g., increasing gradually).

NAME: democimpus
SCENARIO NAME: Democracy impetus by the US/other leadership, 1-10 (10=most); Polity scale
DEFINITION: Democracy impetus by the US/other leadership, 1-10 (10=most); Polity scale
Parameter Explanation: Democracy impetus coming from US or other (e.g., EU) leadership.  Values are on a 1-10 (10=most) scale, related to the Polity democracy scale.  Normally interventions with the parameter would be variable over time (e.g., increasing gradually).

NAME: democimpusn
SCENARIO NAME: Democracy impetus from US, neutral level, 1-10 (10=most); Polity scale
DEFINITION: Democracy impetus from US, neutral level, 1-10 (10=most); Polity scale
Parameter Explanation: The neutral or normal level of democracy impetus coming from US or other (e.g., EU) leadership.  The scale ranges from 1-10 (10=most) and is based on the Polity democracy scale.   Interventions with the parameter would be very uncommon and would normally change its value for all points in time.

NAME: democm
SCENARIO NAME: Democracy level multiplier
DEFINITION: Democracy multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the level of democracy, expressed without units and by region. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, users should not generally  change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: democpolitysetar
DISPLAY NAME: Polity Democracy Index Standard Error Target
SCENARIO NAME: Polity Democracy Index Standard Error Target
DEFINITION: Number of Standard Errors to Target for Polity Democracy Index
Parameter Explanation: This parameter sets the target standard errors to be forecasted for DEMOC. Values range between -2 to 2, with 0 indicating that the target standard errors are turned off. This parameter is used in combination with democpolityseyrtar.

NAME: democpolityseyrtar
DISPLAY NAME: Years to Target Polity Democ Index Standard Error
SCENARIO NAME: Years to Target Polity Democ Index Standard Error
DEFINITION: Years to Target number of Standard Errors for Polity Democracy Index
Parameter Explanation: This parameter sets the number of years to a given standar error target of DEMOC.

NAME: democpolyarchyadd
SCENARIO NAME: Polyarchy Index Additive Factor
DEFINITION: Polyarchy Index Additive Factor
Parameter Explanation: Additive factor to the Polyarchy Index.

NAME: democpolyarchym
SCENARIO NAME: Polyarchy Index Multiplier
DEFINITION: Polyarchy Index Multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on Polyarchy Index

NAME: democwvlen
SCENARIO NAME: Democracy wave length in years (peak to trough/half-wave)
DEFINITION: Democracy wave length in years (peak to trough/half-wave)
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that determines the democracy wave length in years (peak to trough/half-wave).  Historical waves of democracy have been variable in length, so it is very reasonable to speculate that they could change from the base value or over time.

NAME: democwvmax
SCENARIO NAME: Democracy wave, maximum amplitude in Polity scale points
DEFINITION: Democracy wave, maximum amplitude in Polity scale points
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that determines the maximum amplitude in Polity scale points for democracy wave.  Because the Polity democracy scale runs from 1-10 (10=most democratic), it would be highly improbable that the amplitude of any wave be more than 5-6 points.

NAME: desald
DISPLAY NAME: desalination responsiveness to change in price
SCENARIO NAME: desalination responsiveness to change in price
DEFINITION: desalination responsiveness to change in price
Parameter Explanation: Responsiveness of water price to change in prices.

NAME: desali
DISPLAY NAME: desalination responsiveness to change in stock levels of price
SCENARIO NAME: desalination responsiveness to change in stock levels of price
DEFINITION: desalination responsiveness to change in stock levels of price
Parameter Explanation: Responsiveness of water price to change in stock/inventory levels.

NAME: diplodistancetoeu
SCENARIO NAME: Distance to Europe
DEFINITION: Distance to Europe
Parameter Explanation: The physical distance between a country and Europe (Belgium)

NAME: diploembassym
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on Number of Embassies
DEFINITION: Multiplier on Number of Embassies
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on Standarized Number of Embassies that a country can have in other countries in a given year

NAME: diploembassymaxm
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on Maximum Number of Embassies
DEFINITION: Multiplier on Max Number of Embassies that a country can have in other countries in a given year
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on Standarized Maximum Number of Embassies that a country can have in other countries in a given year

NAME: diploigomaxm
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on Maximum Weighted Number of IGOs
DEFINITION: Multiplier on Max Weighted Number of IGOs that a country belongs in a given year
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on Standarized Maximum Weighted Number of Intergovernmental Organizations that a country can belong in a given year

NAME: diploingoadvocacyconv
SCENARIO NAME: Convergence years on INGO Advocacy
DEFINITION: Convergence years  on the number of advocacy INGOs operating in, on or about a country.
Parameter Explanation: Convergence years on the number of advocacy INGOs operating in, on or about a country.

NAME: diploingoadvocacym
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on INGO Advocacy
DEFINITION: Multiplier on the number of advocacy INGOs operating in, on or about a country.
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the number of advocacy INGOs operating in, on or about a country.

NAME: diploingoprogramconv
SCENARIO NAME: Convergence years on INGO Programmatic
DEFINITION: Convergence years on the number of programmatic INGOs operating in, on or about a country.
Parameter Explanation: Convergence years on the number of programmatic INGOs operating in, on or about a country.

NAME: diploingoprogramm
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on INGO Programmatic
DEFINITION: Multiplier on the number of programmatic INGOs operating in, on or about a country.
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the number of programmatic INGOs operating in, on or about a country.

NAME: diplotreatymaxm
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on Maximum Weighted Number of Treaties
DEFINITION: Multiplier on Max Weighted Number of Treaties that a country can sign (1) or ratify (2) in a given year
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier Standarized Maximum Weighted Number of Treaties that a country can sign (1) or ratify (2) in a given year

NAME: dkl
SCENARIO NAME: Depreciation rate of agricultural land investment
DEFINITION: Depreciation coefficient for agricultural land investment
Parameter Explanation: Depreciation coefficient for agricultural land investment.  This scalar (not specific to country/region) indicates the portion (e.g., 0.01 is 1%) of the investment in agricultural land (e.g. terracing or irrigation) that depreciates in a given year.  Raising it would lead to greater requirements of agricultural investment in land to maintain that land in production.

NAME: drcpow
SCENARIO NAME: Depreciation rate of conventional power
DEFINITION: Depreciation rate of conventional power
Parameter Explanation: Annual depreciation rate of conventional power (coefficient).  It is in proportional terms so that 0.1 represents 10% depreciation annually.  High values could simulate arms control agreements that resulted in destruction of weapons.

NAME: drnpow
SCENARIO NAME: Depreciation rate of nuclear power
DEFINITION: Depreciation rate of nuclear power
Parameter Explanation: Annual depreciation rate of nuclear power (coefficient).  It is in proportional terms so that 0.1 represents 10% depreciation annually.  High values could simulate arms control agreements that resulted in destruction of weapons.

NAME: drugglobalconv
SCENARIO NAME: Drug use global convergence rate
DEFINITION: Drug use global convergence rate
Parameter Explanation: Convergence rate in global drug use.

NAME: drugglobalconvsw
SCENARIO NAME: Drug use global convergence switch
DEFINITION: Drug use global convergence switch
Parameter Explanation: Switch for global convergence in drug use.

NAME: druguseamphetaminem
SCENARIO NAME: Amphetamine prevalence multiplier
DEFINITION: Amphetamine prevalence multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the use of amphetamine drug.

NAME: drugusecocainem
SCENARIO NAME: Cocaine prevalence multiplier
DEFINITION: Cocaine prevalence multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier for cocaine use.

NAME: druguseopiatesm
SCENARIO NAME: Opiates prevalence multiplier
DEFINITION: Opiates prevalence multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier for opiate use.

NAME: drugusepolyindex
SCENARIO NAME: Drug use index
DEFINITION: Drug use index
Parameter Explanation: Drug use index.

NAME: druguseprescriptopioidm
SCENARIO NAME: Prescription oioid prevalence multiplier
DEFINITION: Prescription opioid prevalence multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier for prescription opioids.

NAME: dstl
SCENARIO NAME: Desired stock (inventory) level in the economy
DEFINITION: Desired stock (inventory) level in the economy
Parameter Explanation: Desired level of stock or inventory within the economy, represented as a percentage. A value of 0.1, for instance, indicates a target stock level of 10% relative to the base case that often includes annual production and may also encompass demand, exports, or imports.

NAME: dstlen
SCENARIO NAME: Desired level of energy stocks or inventories
DEFINITION: Desired energy stock level as portion of stock base
Parameter Explanation: Desired energy stock level as portion of stock base.  It is in proportional terms so that 0.2 represents a 20% target stock level (of a base that usually includes annual production and may include demand, exports, or imports).  There is little reason for most users to want to change this parameter.

NAME: econfreem
SCENARIO NAME: Economic freedom multiplier
DEFINITION: Economic freedom multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on economic freedom, expressed without units and by region. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: edbudgon
SCENARIO NAME: Education, budget switch (0=budget imapact off, 1= budget impact on, base case)
DEFINITION: Education, budget switch (0=budget imapact off, 1= budget impact on, base case)
Parameter Explanation: Education, parameter to turn budget impact off. Base case value is 1 (=budget impact on). Set it to 0 to bypass budget impacts entirely.

NAME: edenrsecur
SCENARIO NAME: Elasticity of societal insecurity to educational enrollment
DEFINITION: Elasticity of societal insecurity to educational enrollment
Parameter Explanation: Elasticity of the impact of societal insecurity  on enrollment in education.

NAME: edexperprim
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on expenditure per primary student
DEFINITION: Multiplier on expenditure per primary student
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on primary per student expenditure (as % of gdppc).

NAME: edexperseclowrm
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on expenditure per lower secondary student
DEFINITION: Multiplier on expenditure per lower secondary student
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on lower secondary per student expenditure (as % of gdppc).

NAME: edexpersecupprm
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on expenditure per upper secondary student
DEFINITION: Multiplier on expenditure per upper secondary student
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on upper secondary per student expenditure (as % of gdppc).

NAME: edexperterm
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on expenditure per tertiary student
DEFINITION: Multiplier on expenditure per tertiary student
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on tertiary per student expenditure (as % of gdppc).

NAME: edexppconv
SCENARIO NAME: Education pri expenditure per student as % of gdppc convergence time to function
DEFINITION: Education pri expenditure per student as % of gdppc convergence time to function
Parameter Explanation: Primary per student expenditure as % of gdppc convergence time to function in years.  In the base case a shift from the function will be maintained because of the high convergence time.Scenarios with low convergence time make the per student cost rich those of high income countries as countries get richer. This increase in per student cost can come from lower pupil-teacher ratio, higher teacher salary and higher non-teacher salary portion of the cost.

NAME: edexpslconv
SCENARIO NAME: Education Sec Lower exp per student as % of gdppc convergence time to function
DEFINITION: Education Secondary Lower expenditure per student as % of gdppc convergence time to function
Parameter Explanation: Lower Secondary per student  expenditure as % of gdppc convergence time to function in years.  In the base case a shift from the function will be maintained because of the high convergence time.Scenarios with low convergence time make the per student cost rich those of high income countries as countries get richer. This increase in per student cost can come from lower pupil-teacher ratio, higher teacher salary and higher non-teacher salary portion of the cost.

NAME: edexpsuconv
SCENARIO NAME: Education Sec Upper exp per student as % of gdppc convergence time to function
DEFINITION: Education Secondary Upper expenditure per student as % of gdppc convergence time to function
Parameter Explanation: Upper Secondary per student  expenditure as % of gdppc convergence time to function in years.  In the base case a shift from the function will be maintained because of the high convergence time.Scenarios with low convergence time make the per student cost rich those of high income countries as countries get richer. This increase in per student cost can come from lower pupil-teacher ratio, higher teacher salary and higher non-teacher salary portion of the cost.

NAME: edexptconv
SCENARIO NAME: Education ter expenditure per student as % of gdppc convergence time to function
DEFINITION: Education ter expenditure per student as % of gdppc convergence time to function
Parameter Explanation: Tertiary per student expenditure as % of gdppc convergence time to function in years.  In the base case a shift from the function will be maintained because of the high convergence time.Scenarios with low convergence time make the per student cost rich those of high income countries as countries get richer. This increase in per student cost can come from lower pupil-teacher ratio, higher teacher salary and higher non-teacher salary portion of the cost.

NAME: edpricostadjrural
SCENARIO NAME: Education primary, adjustment in per student expenditure for rural areas
DEFINITION: Education primary, adjustment in per student expenditure for rural areas
Parameter Explanation: A multiplier to adjust the marginal unit cost (per student expenditure) of primary education expanding to rural areas

NAME: edprigndreqintn
SCENARIO NAME: Education primary, gender parity time for intake
DEFINITION: Education primary, gender equity time for intake
Parameter Explanation: Education primary, no of years (from firstyear) by which gender parity in net primary intake rate is reached. The gender parity index is the ratio of the male rate to the female rate. Must set edgndreqintnon=1 for this to work.

NAME: edprigndreqsur
SCENARIO NAME: Education primary, gender parity time for survival
DEFINITION: Education primary, gender equity time for survival
Parameter Explanation: Education primary, no of years (from firstyear) by which gender parity in primary survival rate is reached. The gender parity index is the ratio of the male rate to the female rate. Must set edgndreqsuron=1 for this to work.

NAME: edprigoalexper
SCENARIO NAME: Education, primary, per student expenditure goal
DEFINITION: Education, primary, per student expenditure goal
Parameter Explanation: Education Per Primary Student expenditure (as a % of GDPPC) Goal. A parameter to make the countries meet per student expenditure goals, e.g. bes practices. You must set edprigoalexperon to 1 for this to work.

NAME: edprigoalexperon
SCENARIO NAME: Education, primary, normative goal seek, per student expenditure (1=On, 0=Off)
DEFINITION: Education, primary, normative goal seek, per student expenditure (1=On, 0=Off)
Parameter Explanation: Education Per Primary Student expenditure (as a % of GDPPC) Goal Seek Switch. A parameter to turn goal seek on. Works with edprigoalexper

NAME: edpriintngr
SCENARIO NAME: Education, primary, net intake rate, annual growth rate
DEFINITION: Education, primary, net intake rate, annual growth rate
Parameter Explanation: Education Primary Net Intake Rate Anuual Growth Rate. A parameter to make the countries meet education targets by an annual percentage growth in net intake rate.

NAME: edpriintntrgtyr
DISPLAY NAME: Education, Primary, Net Intake Rate, Target Year
SCENARIO NAME: Education, Primary, Net Intake Rate, Target Year
DEFINITION: Education, Primary, Net Intake Rate, Target Year (number of years from base year to reach 100%)
Parameter Explanation: Parameter for the number of years taken to achieve universal net intake rate in primary education.

NAME: edprilen
SCENARIO NAME: Education, primary, duration of primary
DEFINITION: Education, primary, duration of primary
Parameter Explanation: Duration of education, primary is the number of grades (years) in primary education, aggregation rule for group might result in non-integer values

NAME: edpristart
SCENARIO NAME: Education, primary, entrance age to primary
DEFINITION: Education, primary, entrance age to primary
Parameter Explanation: Entrance age in primary education, aggregation rule for group might result in non-integer values

NAME: edprisurgr
SCENARIO NAME: Education, primary, survival rate, annual growth rate
DEFINITION: Education, primary, survival rate, annual growth rate
Parameter Explanation: Education Primary Survival Rate Annual Growth Rate. A parameter to make the countries meet education targets by an annual percentage growth in survival rate.

NAME: edprisurtrgtyr
DISPLAY NAME: Education, Primary, Survival Rate, Target Year
SCENARIO NAME: Education, Primary, Survival Rate, Target Year
DEFINITION: Education, Primary, Survival Rate, Target Year (number of years from base year to reach 100%)
Parameter Explanation: Parameter for the number of years taken to achieve 100% Survival Rate in primary education.

NAME: edseclowrgndreqgrad
SCENARIO NAME: Education lower sec, gender parity time goal for graduation
DEFINITION: Education lower sec, gender parity time goal for graduation
Parameter Explanation: Education lower sec, no of years by which gender parity index for graduation rate reaches 1. The gender parity index is the ratio of the male rate to the female rate. Must set edgndreqsuron=1 for this to work.

NAME: edseclowrgndreqtran
SCENARIO NAME: Education lower sec, gender parity time for transition
DEFINITION: Education lower sec, gender parity time for transition
Parameter Explanation: Education lower sec, no of years by which gender parity index for transition rate raeches 1. The gender parity index is the ratio of the male rate to the female rate.

NAME: edseclowrgradgr
SCENARIO NAME: Education, lower secondary, general, Graduation rate, annual growth
DEFINITION: Education, lower secondary, general, Graduation rate, annual growth parameter
Parameter Explanation: Education, lower secondary (general), Graduation rate to the last grade, annual additive growth. A parameter to make the countries meet education targets by an annual additive growth in the survival rate in general lower secondary.

NAME: edseclowrgratrgtyr
DISPLAY NAME: Education, Sec Lower, Graduation Rate, Target Year
SCENARIO NAME: Education, Sec Lower, Graduation Rate, Target Year
DEFINITION: Education, Sec Lower, Graduation Rate, Target Year (number of years from base year to reach 100%)
Parameter Explanation: Parameter for the number of years taken to achieve 100% Graduation rate from primary to lower secondary education.

NAME: edseclowrlen
DISPLAY NAME: Education, Lower Secondary, Length in Years
DEFINITION: Education, Lower Secondary, Duration
Parameter Explanation: Duration of education, lower secondary is the number of grades (years) in lower secondary education, aggregation rule for group might result in non-integer values

NAME: edseclowrtrangr
SCENARIO NAME: Education, lower secondary, general, transion rate, annual growth
DEFINITION: Education, lower secondary, general, transion rate, annual growth parameter
Parameter Explanation: Education, lower secondary (general), transion rate from primary, annual additive growth. A parameter to make the countries meet education targets by an annual additive growth in the rate of transition from primary to general lower secondary.

NAME: edseclowrtrantrgtyr
DISPLAY NAME: Education, Sec Lower, Transition Rate, Target Year
SCENARIO NAME: Education, Sec Lower, Transition Rate, Target Year
DEFINITION: Education, Sec Lower, Transition Rate, Target Year (number of years from base year to reach 100%)
Parameter Explanation: Parameter for the number of years taken to achieve universal transition rate from primary to lower secondary education.

NAME: edsecupprgndreqgrad
SCENARIO NAME: Education upper sec, gender parity time goal for graduation
DEFINITION: Education upper sec, gender parity, time goal for graduation
Parameter Explanation: Education upper sec, no of years by which gender parity index for graduation rate reaches 1. The gender parity index is the ratio of the male rate to the female rate. Must set edgndreqsuron=1 for this to work.

NAME: edsecupprgndreqtran
SCENARIO NAME: Education upper sec, gender parity time for transition
DEFINITION: Education upper sec, gender parity time for transition
Parameter Explanation: Education upper sec, no of years by which gender parity index for transition rate raeches 1. The gender parity index is the ratio of the male rate to the female rate.

NAME: edsecupprgradgr
SCENARIO NAME: Education, upper secondary, general, Graduation rate, annual growth
DEFINITION: Education, upper secondary, general, Graduation rate, annual growth
Parameter Explanation: Education, upper secondary (general), Graduation rate to the last grade, annual additive growth. A parameter to make the countries meet education targets by an annual additive growth in the survival rate in general upper secondary.

NAME: edsecupprgratrgtyr
DISPLAY NAME: Education, Sec Upper, Graduation Rate, Target Year
SCENARIO NAME: Education, Sec Upper, Graduation Rate, Target Year
DEFINITION: Education, Sec Upper, Graduation Rate, Target Year (number of years from base year to reach 100%)
Parameter Explanation: Parameter for the number of years taken to achieve 100% Graduation rate from primary to upper secondary education.

NAME: edsecupprlen
DISPLAY NAME: Education, Upper Secondary, Length in Years
DEFINITION: Education, Upper Secondary, Duration
Parameter Explanation: Duration of education, Upper secondary is the number of grades (years) in Upper secondary education, aggregation rule for group might result in non-integer values

NAME: edsecupprtrangr
SCENARIO NAME: Education, upper secondary, general, transion rate, annual growth
DEFINITION: Education, upper secondary, general, transion rate, annual growth
Parameter Explanation: Education, upper secondary (general), transion rate from lower secondary, annual additive growth. A parameter to make the countries meet education targets by an annual additive growth in the rate of transition from general lower secondary to general upper secondary.

NAME: edsecupprtrantrgtyr
DISPLAY NAME: Education, Sec Upper, Transition Rate, Target Year
SCENARIO NAME: Education, Sec Upper, Transition Rate, Target Year
DEFINITION: Education, Sec Upper, Transition Rate, Target Year (number of years from base year to reach 100%)
Parameter Explanation: Parameter for the number of years taken to achieve universal transition rate from primary to upper secondary education.

NAME: edtergndreqgrad
SCENARIO NAME: Education tertiary, gender parity time goal for graduation
DEFINITION: Education tertiary, gender parity time goal for graduation
Parameter Explanation: Education tertiary, no of years by which gender parity index for graduation rate reaches 1. The gender parity index is the ratio of the male rate to the female rate. Must set edgndreqsuron=1 for this to work.

NAME: edtergndreqint
SCENARIO NAME: Education tertiary, gender parity time for intake
DEFINITION: Education tertiary, gender parity time for intake
Parameter Explanation: Education tertiary, no of years by which gender parity index for intake rate raeches 1. The gender parity index is the ratio of the male rate to the female rate.

NAME: edtergradtrgtyr
DISPLAY NAME: Education, Tertiary, Graduation Rate, Target Year
SCENARIO NAME: Education, Tertiary, Graduation Rate, Target Year
DEFINITION: Education, Tertiary, Graduation Rate, Target Year (number of years from base year to reach 100%)

NAME: encartpp
SCENARIO NAME: Energy cartel price premium
DEFINITION: Energy cartel price premium
Parameter Explanation: Energy cartel price premium.  This is a parameter (normally 0) that indicates the number of dollars/barrel that an energy cartel could add to global energy prices.  Normally a scenario using this parameter would introduced it for a specific period (e.g., 2020-2025) to represent a tight energy market allowing such a cartel to be effective, at least for a time.

NAME: enconv
SCENARIO NAME: Energy demand convergence time to predicted values
DEFINITION: Energy demand convergence time to predicted values
Parameter Explanation: Energy demand convergence time to predicted values, in years.  Very often initial data values for countries, such as energy demand in this case, will differ a little or much from values predicted by a cross-sectional relationship or other relationship used in the model.  It is never certain whether such differences involve data errors or factors idiosyncratic to countries.  A paradigmatic assumption of IFs is that, over time, values for such variables will often gradually converge to the values predicted by the function and the initial country-specific "shift" should disappear. A high value such as 10000 will effectively turn off the convergence process altogether, while a low value such as 10 will make it very rapid.

NAME: endemm
SCENARIO NAME: Energy demand multiplier
DEFINITION: Energy demand multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Energy demand multiplier.  A multiplier on energy demand, unit-less, by region.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase demand and lower values decrease it.

NAME: enelecshrendemm
DISPLAY NAME: Electricity Share of Energy Use Multiplier
SCENARIO NAME: Electricity as a Percentage of Energy Use, Multiplier
DEFINITION: Electricity as a Percentage of Energy Multiplier

NAME: eninvadd
SCENARIO NAME: Energy investment additive factor
DEFINITION: Energy investment additive factor
Parameter Explanation: Energy investment additive factor.  An additive factor on energy investment, in Billion $, by region.  A value of 0 implies no change, while positive values increase investment and negative values decrease it.

NAME: eninvm
SCENARIO NAME: Energy investment multiplier
DEFINITION: Energy investment multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Energy investment multiplier.  A multiplier on energy investment, unit-less, by region.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase investment and lower values decrease it.

NAME: eninvtm
SCENARIO NAME: Energy investment by energy type multiplier
DEFINITION: Energy investment by energy type multiplier (shifts within total)
Parameter Explanation: Energy investment by type multiplier.  A multiplier on energy investment by type, unit-less, by region.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase investment and lower values decrease it.  This parameter does not increase or decrease total energy investment; see eninvm for that.

NAME: enml
SCENARIO NAME: Energy imports limit
DEFINITION: Energy import limit
Parameter Explanation: Energy import limit, expressed in billion barrels of oil equivalent functions both as a switch and a numerical value, with 0 indicating no limit and positive values setting a specific limit. Positive values (above .001) limit imports to the value specified.  For instance, a specification for a country of 0 for the first five years, 2 for the next three, and 0 thereafter,  introduces a constrain on imports of two billion barrels per year during the sixth, seventh, and eighth years.  Restrictions of this kind are more often posed by exporters (see enxl) than importers.

NAME: enmm
SCENARIO NAME: Energy imports multiplier
DEFINITION: Energy imports multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on energy imports, by region. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase imports and lower values decrease them.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: ennoprodsw
DISPLAY NAME: Energy no production switch (1 turns off production of energy)
SCENARIO NAME: Energy no production switch (1 turns off production of energy)
DEFINITION: Energy no production switch (1 turns off production of energy)
Parameter Explanation: Energy no production switch (1 turns off production of energy)

NAME: enon
SCENARIO NAME: Energy-economy linkage switch (On=1/Off=0)
DEFINITION: Energy-economy linkage switch (On=1/Off=0)
Parameter Explanation: Energy switch.  This switch turns on or off the linkages between the energy submodel and all others, including economics.  When off, the economic model relies upon the simpler structure of its own energy sector.  The switch enon takes values only of 1 (on) and 0 (off).  It is often useful to disconnect submodels while exploring the behavior of any one.  The normal value is 1.

NAME: enpadd
SCENARIO NAME: Energy production additive factor
DEFINITION: Energy production additive factor
Parameter Explanation: Energy production additive factor.  An additve factor on all types of energy production, unit-less, by region.  A value of 0 implies no change, while positive values proportionately increase production and negative values decrease it.  Warning: no cost to increased production; see ENINVM and ENINVTM for parameters to shift investment and production with trade-offs.

NAME: enpcoalmax
SCENARIO NAME: Energy production, coal maximum production

NAME: enpgasmax

DEFINITION: Energy production multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Energy production multiplier.  A multiplier on all types of energy production, unit-less, by region.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase production and lower values decrease it.  Warning: no cost to increased production; see ENINVM and ENINVTM for parameters to shift investment and production with trade-offs.

NAME: enpoilmax
SCENARIO NAME: Energy production, oil maximum production
DEFINITION: Energy production, oil maximum production

NAME: enprix
SCENARIO NAME: Energy price override
DEFINITION: Exogenous energy price when set above 0.0
Parameter Explanation: Energy price in dollars per barrel of oil equivalent, by region.  Energy price (ENPRI) is normally computed endogenously so as to balance supply and demand of energy.  If you set enprix to positive, nonzero values, you can override the endogenous computation with your own price level.  It is possible to intervene with energy prices only for select years by leaving enprix at zero for other years and specifying enprix only for selected ones.  You might do this, for instance, to represent a period in which government controls energy prices domestically or a cartel sets them internationally.

NAME: enprixi
SCENARIO NAME: Energy price override, initial or equilibrium base
DEFINITION: Exogenous initial or equilibium base energy price when set above 0.0
Parameter Explanation: Energy base equilibium price in dollars per barrel of oil equivalent, by region.  Energy price (ENPRI) is normally computed relative to a price given in the initial or base year.  If that price is consdered far from long-term equilibirum, this parameter can overide it endogenously.  If you set enprixi to positive, nonzero values, you can override the initial oil price with your own price level.

NAME: enresunce

Parameter Explanation: Annual percentage change in energy demand as a result of technological change.  This parameter helps represent the historic phenomenon of considerable decrease over time in energy requirements per unit of economic output ("dematerialization").  It is an uncertain but very important parameter.  A value of -1 would represent an annual efficiency improvement of 1 percent.
