NAME: enxl
SCENARIO NAME: Energy exports limit
DEFINITION: Energy export limit
Parameter Explanation: Energy export limit, ex billion barrels of oil equivalent  functions both as a switch and a numerical value, with 0 indicating no limit and positive values setting a specific limit..  Positive values (above .001) limit exports to the value specified.  For instance, a specification for a country of 0 for the first five years, 2 for the next three, and 0 thereafter,  introduces a constrain on exports of two billion barrels per year during the sixth, seventh, and eighth years.  If placed on OPEC exports, such an export restriction would be very severe.

NAME: enxm
SCENARIO NAME: Energy exports multiplier
DEFINITION: Energy exports multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on energy exports, by region. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase exports and lower values decrease them.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: epra
SCENARIO NAME: Energy price responsiveness to stock/inventory levels
DEFINITION: Energy price responsiveness to stock/inventory levels
Parameter Explanation: Energy price responsiveness to stock/inventory levels.  Epra and eprafs are a pair of adjustment parameters (not true elasticities), most of which normally have about a 1:2 ratio.  Significant changes in this parameter could destabilize model behavior.

NAME: eprafs
SCENARIO NAME: Energy price responsiveness to change in stock/inventory levels
DEFINITION: Energy price responsiveness to change in stock/inventory levels
Parameter Explanation: Energy price responsiveness to change in stock/inventory levels

NAME: eprodr
SCENARIO NAME: Energy production growth rate
DEFINITION: Energy production growth rate
Parameter Explanation: Energy production growth rate, expressed in decimal form (e.g., 0.035 equals 3.5 percent annual growth, by region and fuel type. This parameter can override endogenous patterns of energy production growth and force a pattern of growth for a specific fuel or set of fuels.  Growth rates are, however, constrained in the model by the availability of investment and/or resources, and may not be met.  Only positive values are allowed.  Under most circumstances, the initial value for this variable should be equal to that of enprr for the specified region and fuel type, because enprr is the empirical initial growth rate.

NAME: eprohw
SCENARIO NAME: Energy profits, historic (inertial delay) in impact on investment
DEFINITION: Energy historical weight for profits in investment
Parameter Explanation: Energy profits, historic (inertial delay) in impact on investment.  Values near 1.0 imply very rapid adjustment and values near 0 imply little or no adjustment.  Significant changes in this parameter could destabilize model behavior.

NAME: etechadvuncon
SCENARIO NAME: Unconventional energy production technology, annual decease in cost
DEFINITION: Unconventional energy production technology, annual decease in cost
DISPLAY UNITS: Annual Decrease in Energy Production Cost
Parameter Explanation: Unconventional energy technology advance rate (decrease in cost of energy production), expressed in decimal form (e.g. 0.01 equals 1 percent annual growth, by energy type).  Use, for example, to decrease the cost of renewable energy over time.  A value of 0.01 applied to renewable energy would force an annual decrease in the costs of producing solar energy of 1% each year, representing continued technological advance in such production (a value of -0.01 would represent a negative cost decrease, that is, a cost increase).

NAME: eumembsw
SCENARIO NAME: EU membership switch for caculations of power (0=none; 1= member)
DEFINITION: EU membership switch for caculations of power (0=none; 1= member)
Parameter Explanation: EU membership switch for caculations of power (0=none; 1= member).  The members of the European Union are, of course, known.  But as candidate members become full members, it would be appropriate to change the values of this parameter.

NAME: exomerpppmatchsw
SCENARIO NAME: Used to swap between GDPPOT and GDP in ifsEcoPPP
DEFINITION: Value of zero preserves GDPPOT in ifsEcoPPP; Other values force GDP to be used instead. This is a part of the two-run exogenous sceanrio workflow.
Parameter Explanation: Value of zero preserves GDPPOT in ifsEcoPPP; Other values force GDP to be used instead. This is a part of the two-run exogenous sceanrio workflow.

NAME: feddemm
SCENARIO NAME: Livestock feed demand multiplier
DEFINITION: Livestock feed demand demand multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on all livestock feed demand, by region and without units. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase demand and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: femshrgr
SCENARIO NAME: Female share of labor force, annual % growth rate
DEFINITION: Female share of the labor force, annual growth rate
Parameter Explanation: Annual growth rate of the female share in the labor force, expressed in percentage terms.

NAME: firmtaxrm
SCENARIO NAME: Firm tax rate multiplier
DEFINITION: Firm tax rate multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government taxes imposed on firms, expressed without units and by region. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase taxes and lower values decrease them.

NAME: fishcatchm
SCENARIO NAME: Fish catch multiplier
DEFINITION: Fish catch multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on fish catch (freshwater and marine) unit-less, by region.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase demand and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: forestm
SCENARIO NAME: Forest protection multiplier
DEFINITION: Forest protection multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on forest area, by region, expressed without units. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase forest area and lower values decrease it.

NAME: fpricr1
SCENARIO NAME: Food prices, response to stock level
DEFINITION: Food prices, response to stock level
Parameter Explanation: Elasticity of food prices (crops) to stock level. Frpricr1 and fpricr2 are a pair of adjustment parameters, most of which normally have about a 1:2 ratio.  Significant changes in this parameter could destabilize model behavior.

NAME: fpricr2
SCENARIO NAME: Food prices, response to change in stock level
DEFINITION: Food prices, response to change in stock level
Parameter Explanation: Elasticity of food prices (crops) to changes in stock level. Frpricr1 and fpricr2 are a pair of adjustment parameters, most of which normally have about a 1:2 ratio.  Significant changes in this parameter could destabilize model behavior.

NAME: fprihw
SCENARIO NAME: Food prices, historic (inertial delay) in change
DEFINITION: Food prices, historic (inertial delay) in change
Parameter Explanation: Historic (inertial delay) change in food prices. Values close to 1 imply very rapid adjustment and values near 0 imply little or no adjustment.  Significant changes in this parameter could destabilize model behavior.

NAME: fprimt1
SCENARIO NAME: Food prices (meat), response to stock level
DEFINITION: Food prices (meat), response to stock level
Parameter Explanation: Elasticity of food prices (meat) to stock level. Fprimt1 and fprimt2 are a pair of adjustment parameters, most of which normally have about a 1:2 ratio.  Significant changes in this parameter could destabilize model behavior.

NAME: fprimt2
SCENARIO NAME: Food prices (meat), response to changes in stock level
DEFINITION: Food prices (meat), response to changes in stock level
Parameter Explanation: Elasticity of food prices (meat) to changes in stock level. Fprimt1 and fprimt2 are a pair of adjustment parameters, most of which normally have about a 1:2 ratio.  Significant changes in this parameter could destabilize model behavior.

NAME: freedomm
SCENARIO NAME: Freedom (political) multiplier
DEFINITION: Freedom multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on Freedom House's measure of freedom (FREEDOM), which combines civil and political scale ranging from 2 (most free) to 14 (least free). A value of 1 in the multiplier implies no change, while higher values increase the value of FREEDOM (making a country/region less free).

NAME: gdpadjsw
SCENARIO NAME: GDP Adjustment Switch
DEFINITION: GDP Adjustment Switch (0 protects gdprext fully; 1 uses base case adjust plus scenarios)
Parameter Explanation: Switch to turn on endogenous changes on GDP over external growth rates.  If the switch is on, any scenario changes (including gdprext, mfpadd, gdsm) will affect gdpr on top of base case adjustment related to gdprest; if full control in scenarios is wanted with gdprext (new values will totally control gdpr), set switch to 0 simultaneously when making such full control changes with gdprext

NAME: gdpinformcoeffcorrupt
SCENARIO NAME: Informal GDP share, coefficient of Corruption
DEFINITION: Informal GDP share, coefficient of Corruption
Parameter Explanation: This parameter is used to change the coefficient of Corruption Index  in the multiple regression of informal GDP shares.

NAME: gdpinformcoeffintercept
SCENARIO NAME: Informal GDP share, intercept of regression model
DEFINITION: Informal GDP share, intercept of regression model
Parameter Explanation: This parameter is used to change the intercept of the multiple regression of informal GDP shares.

NAME: gdpinformcoefflabinf
SCENARIO NAME: Informal GDP share, coefficient of Informal Labor Share
DEFINITION: Informal GDP share, coefficient of Informal Labor Share
Parameter Explanation: This parameter is used to change the coefficient of Informal Labor Share  in the multiple regression of informal GDP shares.

NAME: gdpinformcoeffrand
SCENARIO NAME: Informal GDP share, coefficient of R&D spending
DEFINITION: Informal GDP share, coefficient of Total R&D spending
Parameter Explanation: This parameter is used to change the coefficient of R & D spending (total, as a % of GDP)  in the multiple regression of informal GDP shares.

NAME: gdpinformshrm
SCENARIO NAME: Informal GDP share multiplier
DEFINITION: Informal GDP share multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the informal share of GDP.

NAME: gdprext
SCENARIO NAME: GDP growth rate, exogenous target (percent); use with gdpadjsw=0
DEFINITION: GDP growth rate, exogenous target (percent); use with gdpadjsw=0
Parameter Explanation: Computed in the preprocessor to set economic growth rates exogenously in early model years; it should be set to 0 when using gdpadjsw to determine growth.

NAME: gdpshadowcoeffcorrupt
SCENARIO NAME: Shadow (Informal) GDP share model, coefficient of Corruption
DEFINITION: Shadow (Informal) GDP share model, coefficient of Corruption
Parameter Explanation: This parameter is used to change the coefficient of Corruption Index  in the multiple regression of shadow (informal) GDP shares.

NAME: gdpshadowcoeffintercept
SCENARIO NAME: Shadow (Informal) GDP share model, intercept of regression model
DEFINITION: Shadow (Informal) GDP share model, intercept of regression model
Parameter Explanation: This parameter is used to change the intercept of the multiple regression of shadow (informal) GDP shares.

NAME: gdpshadowcoefflabinf
SCENARIO NAME: Shadow (Informal) GDP share model, coefficient of Informal Labor Share
DEFINITION: Shadow (Informal) GDP share model, coefficient of Informal Labor Share
Parameter Explanation: This parameter is used to change the coefficient of Informal Labor Share in the multiple regression of shadow (informal) GDP shares.

NAME: gdpshadowcoeffrand
SCENARIO NAME: Shadow (Informal) GDP share model, coefficient of R&D spending
DEFINITION: Shadow (Informal) GDP share model, coefficient of Total R&D spending
Parameter Explanation: This parameter is used to change the coefficient of R & D spending (total, as a % of GDP)  in the multiple regression of shadow (informal) GDP shares.

NAME: gdpshadowon
SCENARIO NAME: Shadow/Informal Switch (1=Shadow, 0=Informal)
DEFINITION: Shadow/Informal Switch (1=Shadow, 0=Informal)
Parameter Explanation: Switch for Shadow/Informal economy. A value of  1 turns on  the shadow economy, 0 turns on the informal economy (as in the base case)

NAME: gdpshadowshrm
SCENARIO NAME: Shadow (Informal) Economy share multiplier
DEFINITION: Shadow (informal) economy share multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the shadow (informal) GDP share.

NAME: gdscnstsw
SCENARIO NAME: Government expenditures by destination switch to keep constant
DEFINITION: Government expenditures by destination  switch to keep constant
Parameter Explanation: Government expenditures by destination  switch to keep constant.  A value of 1 implies switch is on, meaning GDS%GDP should be kept constant over time.

NAME: gdsedm
SCENARIO NAME: Government expenditures on education by level, multiplier
DEFINITION: Government expenditures on education by level, multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government expenditure on education by level.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: gdsm
SCENARIO NAME: Government expenditures by destination multiplier
DEFINITION: Government expenditures by destination multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government expenditure by destination.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: gdsnormalize
SCENARIO NAME: Government Finance Model Normalization Switch (1=On, 0=Off)
DEFINITION: Government Finance Model Normalization Switch (1=On, 0=Off) (needs rebuild of base)
Parameter Explanation: Switch for government finance model normalizatio. The base value of 1 normalizes all GDS to GOVCON, while a value of 0 allocates whatever is demanded by GDS and GOVCON does not get affected.

NAME: gemm
SCENARIO NAME: Gender empowerment measure multiplier
DEFINITION: Gender empowerment measure multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the Gender Empowerment Measure (GEM).

NAME: gemsetar
DISPLAY NAME: Gender Empowerment Measure Standard Error Target
SCENARIO NAME: Gender Empowerment Measure Standard Error Target
DEFINITION: Number of Standard Errors to Target for Gender Empowerment Measure
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the target standard errors for GEM forecast. Value range between -2 to 2, with 0 indicating that the target is turned off. Used in combination with gemseytar.

NAME: gemseyrtar
DISPLAY NAME: Years to Target GEM Standard Error
SCENARIO NAME: Years to Target Gender Empowerment Measure Standard Error
DEFINITION: Years to Target number of Standard Errors for Gender Empowerment Measure
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies that number of years to reach the standard error target for GEM.

NAME: ginidomcnstsw
SCENARIO NAME: Domestic Gini Switch to keep constant (1 is on, and it can start at any year)
DEFINITION: Domestic Gini Switch to keep constant (1 is on, and it can start at any year)
Parameter Explanation: Domestic Gini Index constant switch.  Values of 0 turn off and allow endogenous computation; 1 starts the consant period with the last saved value.

NAME: ginidomm
SCENARIO NAME: Domestic Gini, multiplier
DEFINITION: Domestic Gini, multiplier (Base is equal to 1)
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on domestic Gini Index.

NAME: ginidomr
SCENARIO NAME: Domestic Gini, ratio to intial condition (0 turns off, computes endogenously)
DEFINITION: Domestic Gini, ratio to intial condition (0 turns off, computes endogenously)
Parameter Explanation: Rate of change in the domestic Gini Index. Values of 0 turn off and allow endogenous computation; non-zero values are applied to initial conditions like normal multipliers.

NAME: globalfundsrecipients
DISPLAY NAME: Global Fund Receipients (1 is on, 0 is off)
SCENARIO NAME: Global Fund Receipients (1 is on, 0 is off)
DEFINITION: Global Fund Receipients (1 is on, 0 is off)
Parameter Explanation: Switch for global fund recipients. A value of 1 indicates on; 0 indicates off.

NAME: glocom
SCENARIO NAME: Global community multiplier
DEFINITION: Global community multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Global community multiplier.  This global (not regional) parameter affects the probability of war  between any two geographic actors.   A value of 1 leaves the base probability unchanged.  A value of 1.5 would increase "community" by 50 percent and thereby decrease the probability of war by 50 percent.  A value of 0.5 would suggest a deterioration in global community.

NAME: govbuscostm
SCENARIO NAME: Cost of starting a business multiplier
DEFINITION: Cost of starting a business multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the cost of starting a business.

NAME: govbusregindm
SCENARIO NAME: Government regulation of business index multiplier
DEFINITION: Government regulation of business index multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the level of government regulation of Business Index.

NAME: govconm
SCENARIO NAME: Government consumption multiplier
DEFINITION: Government consumption multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government consumption. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: govconswing
DISPLAY NAME: Government Consumption, Readjust Total from Destination Sectors
SCENARIO NAME: Government Consumption, Readjust Total from Destination Sectors
DEFINITION: Government Consumption, Readjust Total from Destination Sectors
Parameter Explanation: This parameter brings in convergence between development function determined spending and demand side (bottom-up) calculation of spending.

NAME: govcorruptm
SCENARIO NAME: Government corruption, multiplier
DEFINITION: Government corruption, multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government corruption index.

NAME: govcorruptsetar
SCENARIO NAME: Government Corruption Measure Standard Error Target
DEFINITION: Number of Standard Errors to Target for Government Corruption
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the target standard errors for GOVCORRUPT forecast. Value range between -2 to 2, with 0 indicating that the target is turned off. Used in combination with govcorruptseyrtar.

NAME: govcorruptseyrtar
DISPLAY NAME: Years to Target Gov Corrupt Standard Error
SCENARIO NAME: Years to Target Government Corruption Standard Error
DEFINITION: Years to Target number of Standard Errors for Government Corruption
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies that number of years to reach the standard error target for GOVCORRUPT.

NAME: govdebtchg
SCENARIO NAME: Government debt change, wo revenues or expenditures specified
DEFINITION: Government debt change, wo revenues or expenditures specified (e.g. relief of debt or population)
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that represents an additive factor for Government debt change as % of GDP. It can represent relief by debt holders or expenditures in crisis with no net addition to recipient finances.  A value of 0 implies no net debt change by exogenous assumption.

NAME: goveffconv
SCENARIO NAME: Government effectiveness, convergence time to expected value
DEFINITION: Government effectiveness, convergence time to expected value
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that determines the convergence time of government effectiveness to its expected value. Very often initial data values for countries will differ a little or much from values predicted by a cross-sectional relationship.  It is never certain whether such differences involve data errors or factors idiosyncratic to countries.  A paradigmatic assumption of IFs is that, over time, values for such variables will often gradually converge to the values predicted by the function and the initial country-specific "shift" should disappear. A high value such as 10000 will effectively turn off the convergence process altogether, while a low value such as 10 will make it very rapid.

NAME: goveffectm
SCENARIO NAME: Government effectiveness (quality), multiplier
DEFINITION: Government effectiveness (quality), multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government effectiveness index.

NAME: goveffectsetar
SCENARIO NAME: Government Effectiveness Measure Standard Error Target
DEFINITION: Number of Standard Errors to Target for Government Effectiveness
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the target standard errors for GOVEFFECT forecast. Value range between -2 to 2, with 0 indicating that the target is turned off. Used in combination with goveffectseyrtar.

NAME: goveffectseyrtar
DISPLAY NAME: Years to Target Gov Effect Standard Error
SCENARIO NAME: Years to Target Government Effectiveness Standard Error
DEFINITION: Years to Target number of Standard Errors for Government Effectiveness
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies that number of years to reach the standard error target for GOVEFFECT.

NAME: govexpm
SCENARIO NAME: Government expenditures multiplier
DEFINITION: Government expenditures multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government expenditure by destination.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: govfinconv
SCENARIO NAME: Government financial balances, convergence time to global functions
DEFINITION: Government financial balances, convergence time to global functions
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that determines the convergence time of government financial balances to its global function. Very often initial data values for countries will differ a little or much from values predicted by a cross-sectional relationship.  It is never certain whether such differences involve data errors or factors idiosyncratic to countries.  A paradigmatic assumption of IFs is that, over time, values for such variables will often gradually converge to the values predicted by the function and the initial country-specific "shift" should disappear. A high value such as 10000 will effectively turn off the convergence process altogether, while a low value such as 10 will make it very rapid.

NAME: govhhpentndpctuse
DISPLAY NAME: Percent used of needed government pensions
SCENARIO NAME: Percent used of needed government pensions
DEFINITION: Government to household transfers needed for pensions, total
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the target percentage of the required government transfers (pensions) to households, under assumptions of aging burdens.

NAME: govindsecurconflict
DISPLAY NAME: Multiplier on Government security index term (Conflict)
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on Government security index term (Conflict)
DEFINITION: Government security index term (Conflict term)
Parameter Explanation: Government security index term for conflict.

NAME: govindsecurgovrisk
DISPLAY NAME: Multiplier on Government security index term (Government risk)
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on Government security index term (Government risk)
DEFINITION: Government security index term (Government risk term)
Parameter Explanation: Government security index term for for government risk.

NAME: govindsecurm
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on Government Security Index
DEFINITION: Multiplier on Government Security Index
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government security index.

NAME: govindsecurviolence
DISPLAY NAME: Multiplier on Government security index term (Violence)
SCENARIO NAME: Multiplier on Government security index term (Violence)
DEFINITION: Government security index term (Violence term)
Parameter Explanation: Government security index term for for violence.

NAME: govnucwpadd
SCENARIO NAME: Number of nuclear weapons addition
DEFINITION: Number of nuclear weapons addition
Parameter Explanation: Adds to or subtracts from the number of nuclear weapons countries have

NAME: govregqualm
SCENARIO NAME: Government regulatory quality multiplier
DEFINITION: Government regulatory quality multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government regulatory quality index.

NAME: govregqualsetar
DISPLAY NAME: Gov. regulatory quality Standard Error Target
SCENARIO NAME: Gov. regulatory quality Standard Error Target
DEFINITION: Number of Standard Errors to Target for Gov. regulatory quality
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the target standard errors for GOVREGQUAL forecast. Value range between -2 to 2, with 0 indicating that the target is turned off. Used in combination with govregqualseyrtar.

NAME: govregqualseyrtar
DISPLAY NAME: Years to Target Gov. Reg quality Standard Error
SCENARIO NAME: Years to Target Gov. Reg quality Standard Error
DEFINITION: Years to Target number of Standard Errors for Gov. regulatory quality
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies that number of years to reach the standard error target for GOVREGQUAL.

NAME: govrevm
SCENARIO NAME: Government revenues multiplier
DEFINITION: Government revenues multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government revenues by destination. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: govrevtrgtval
DISPLAY NAME: Government Revenue, Target Value as a Percent of GDP
SCENARIO NAME: Government Revenue, Target Value as a Percentage of GDP
DEFINITION: Government Revenue, Target Value as Percentage of GDP
Parameter Explanation: This parameter specifies the target value for government revenue collection, expressed as a percentage of GDP. It is used in combination with govrevtrgtyr that defines the number of years to reach the target value from the initial year.

NAME: govrevtrgtyr
SCENARIO NAME: Government Revenue, no of Years to Raise Revenue Collection to a Target Level
DEFINITION: Government Revenue, no of years to Raise Revenue Collection to a Target Level
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the number of years starting from the initial year by which government revenue collection reaches the target level defined by the parameter govrevtrgltlv.

NAME: govriskm
SCENARIO NAME: Governance Security Risk Multiplier
DEFINITION: Multiplier of government risk
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government risk, and this affects governance security index and government quality index.

NAME: govriskweight
SCENARIO NAME: Performance and Risk Index Weights (used in the calculation of the risk idnex)
DEFINITION: Performance and Risk Index Weights (used in the calculation of the risk idnex)
Parameter Explanation: The Risk Index is a weigthed average of the contribution to risk of a set of aproximately 20 variables. Each variable can contribute from 0 to 1 depending on where its value sits in the Minimum to Maximum range. The weights can take any value.

NAME: hdiedslemaxun
SCENARIO NAME: Education, school life expectancy, maximum for HDI, set by UNDP
DEFINITION: Education, school life expectancy, maximum for HDI, set by UNDP
Parameter Explanation: This parameter determines the maximum school life expectancy in education, used for calculation of education component in HDI. Users will normally not change this parameter.

NAME: hdiedsleminun
SCENARIO NAME: Education, school life expectancy, mnimum for HDI, set by UNDP
DEFINITION: Education, school life expectancy, minimum for HDI, set by UNDP
Parameter Explanation: This parameter determines the minimum school life expectancy in education, used for calculation of education component in HDI. Users will normally not change this parameter.

NAME: hdiedyrsmaxun
SCENARIO NAME: Education, average years of 25+, maximum for HDI, set by UNDP
DEFINITION: Education, average years of 25+, maximum for HDI, set by UNDP
Parameter Explanation: This parameter determines the maximum education years for adults aged over 25, used for calculation of education component in HDI. Users will normally not change this parameter.

NAME: hdiedyrsminun
SCENARIO NAME: Education, average years of 25+, minimum for HDI, set by UNDP
DEFINITION: Education, average years of 25+, minimum for HDI, set by UNDP
Parameter Explanation: This parameter determines the minimum education years for adults aged over 25, used for calculation of education component in HDI. Users will normally not change this parameter.

NAME: hdigdppcmax
SCENARIO NAME: GDP per capita maximum for 21st century HDI calculation, fixed
DEFINITION: GDP per capita maximum for 21st century HDI calculation, fixed
Parameter Explanation: GDP per capita calculation for HDI calculation in thousands.  Users may change the parameter to represent changing global possibilities..

NAME: hdigdppcmaxun
SCENARIO NAME: GDP per capita maximum for HDI, by gender, set by UNDP
DEFINITION: GDP per capita maximum for HDI, by gender, set by UNDP
Parameter Explanation: This parameter determines the maximum GDP per capita, used for calculation of  HDI component. Users will normally not change this parameter.

NAME: hdigdppcminun

DEFINITION: GDP per capita minimum for HDI, by gender, set by UNDP
Parameter Explanation: This parameter determines the minimum GDP per capita, used for calculation of  HDI component. Users will normally not change this parameter.

NAME: hdilifemax

DEFINITION: Life expectancy maximum for HDI calculation

NAME: hdilifemaxf

DEFINITION: Life expectancy maximum for 21st century HDI calculation, fixed
Parameter Explanation: Life expectancy minimum for HDI calculation, in years.  Users may change the parameter to represent growing life expectancy.

NAME: hdilifemaxun
SCENARIO NAME: Life expectancy maximum for HDI, by gender, set by UNDP
DEFINITION: Life expectancy maximum for HDI, by gender, set by UNDP
Parameter Explanation: This parameter determines the maximum life expectancy, used for calculation of  HDI component. Users will normally not change this parameter.

NAME: hdilifeminun
SCENARIO NAME: Life expectancy minimum for HDI, by gender, set by UNDP
DEFINITION: Life expectancy minimum for HDI, by gender, set by UNDP
Parameter Explanation: This parameter determines the minimum life expectancy, used for calculation of  HDI component. Users will normally not change this parameter.

NAME: hhsaveneedrat
SCENARIO NAME: Ratio of accumulated savings to Integrated need for pensions
DEFINITION: Ratio of accumulated savings to Integrated need for pensions
Parameter Explanation: Allows the user to create an initial discrepancy between accumulated savings (HHSAVSTOCK) and integrated need (HHSAVNEEDSTOCK).

NAME: hhsizem
SCENARIO NAME: Household size, multiplier
DEFINITION: Household size, numbe of people in a household, multiplier on

NAME: hivincr
SCENARIO NAME: HIV infection rate, annual increase rate during historic period
DEFINITION: HIV infection rate, annual increase rate during historic period
Parameter Explanation: Annual increase in the HIV infection rate during historic period, expressed in percentage terms. A value of 8 means an annual increase rate of 8% and these values are only used in the period prior to 2000.

NAME: hivm
SCENARIO NAME: HIV infection rate of advance, multliplier
DEFINITION: HIV infection rate of advance, multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on HIV infection rate. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: hivpeakr
SCENARIO NAME: HIV infection rate at year of epidemic peak
DEFINITION: HIV infection rate at year of epidemic peak
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the peak rate of HIV infection. It controls the highest rate of infection in a population before the epidemic begins to wane.

NAME: hivpeakyr
SCENARIO NAME: HIV, year of epidemic peak
DEFINITION: HIV, year of epidemic peak
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the peak year of HIV infection. It controls the year in which the rate of infection in a population reaches its peak, before the epidemic begins to wane.

NAME: hivtadvr
SCENARIO NAME: HIV, technical advance rate in control of infection
DEFINITION: HIV technical control, annual advance in infection rate reduction
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the HIV technical advance rate to control spread of infection. This reflects simulation of social and behavioral change.

NAME: hlbednetsm
DISPLAY NAME: Bednets coverage of age under 5 multiplier
SCENARIO NAME: Bednets coverage of age under 5 multiplier
DEFINITION: Bednets coverage of age under 5 multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on availability of bednet. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: hlcomaddmort

DEFINITION: Comm. Dis. Mortality to Add
Parameter Explanation: Communicable Disease Mortality to be added exogenously to Other Communicable Diseases.

NAME: hlcomaddprev
SCENARIO NAME: Comm. Dis. Prevalence to Add
DEFINITION: Comm. Dis. Prevalence to Add
Parameter Explanation: Communicable Disease Prevalence to be added exogenously to Other Communicable Diseases.

NAME: hlcondomusem
DISPLAY NAME: Condom use by 15-24 year-old males in high-risk sex, multiplier
SCENARIO NAME: Condom use 15-24 year-old males in high-risk sex, multiplier
DEFINITION: Condom use 15-24 year-old males in high-risk sex, multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the use of condoms among 15-24 year olds in high risk-sex cases. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: hlcostgrowthel
SCENARIO NAME: Cost Growth elasticity
DEFINITION: Cost Growth elasticity
Parameter Explanation: This parameter controls the growth of health cost, which is managed by GDPPC growth, so if GDPPC growth if 10%, and elasticity is 0.5 then cost growth will be 5%.

NAME: hlcostletime
SCENARIO NAME: Life Extension Treatment Duration
DEFINITION: Life Extension Treatment Duration

NAME: malnchpsamadj
SCENARIO NAME: Severe Acute Malnutrition Incidence adjustment
DEFINITION: Severe Acute Malnutrition Incidence adjustment
Parameter Explanation: Adjustment parameter for incidence of Severe Acute Malnutrition (SAM).  A value of 1 represents Incidence is equal to prevalence. Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: malnchpsamm
SCENARIO NAME: Severe Acute Malnutrition, multiplier
DEFINITION: Severe Acute Malnutrition, multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on Severe Acute Malnutrition (SAM).  A value of 1 represents no change, 1.25 represents a 25 percent increase and .75 represents a 25 percent decrease.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: malnchpsamtostunt
DISPLAY NAME: Severe Acute Malnutrition effect on Stunting
SCENARIO NAME: Severe Acute Malnutrition effect on stunting
DEFINITION: Severe Acute Malnutrition effect on stunting
Parameter Explanation: Elasticity of SAM on stunting. This parameter is used to increase or decrease the effect of severe acute malnutrition on stunting.

NAME: malnconv
SCENARIO NAME: Malnutrition, convergence time to expected value
DEFINITION: Malnutrition, convergence time to expected value
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that determines the convergence time of political variables to its expected value.  Very often initial data values for countries will differ a little or much from values predicted by a cross-sectional relationship.  It is never certain whether such differences involve data errors or factors idiosyncratic to countries.  A paradigmatic assumption of IFs is that, over time, values for such variables will often gradually converge to the values predicted by the function and the initial country-specific "shift" should disappear. A high value such as 10000 will effectively turn off the convergence process altogether, while a low value such as 10 will make it very rapid.

NAME: malnelimstartyr
SCENARIO NAME: Begin year for an elimination of hunger scenario - works with malnelimtargetyr
DEFINITION: Begin year for an elimination of hunger scenario - works with malnelimtargetyr
Parameter Explanation: This parameter specifies the starting year towards elimination of hunger. It works in combination with malnelimtargetyr.

NAME: malnelimtargetyr
SCENARIO NAME: Target year for an elimination of hunger scenario - works with malnelimstartyr

Parameter Explanation: This parameter specifies the target year towards elimination of hunger. It works in combination with malnelimstarttyr.

NAME: malnm

Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: marmsm

The normal value is zero.  See also and contrast with cultshmp, which is a cultural shift for the large cultural regions identified in the WVS project and which is calculated from data.

This parameter is a powerful mechanism by which the user can increase or decrease the growth rate of countries around assumptions of the rate of productivity growth.  Normally values would be 0.0.  A value of 0.01 would introduce an added productivity growth of 1.0% annually.

SCENARIO NAME: Migration rate (inward), percent of population
DEFINITION: Migration rate (inward), percent of population
Parameter Explanation: Net migration of a population in percent per year (negative values reflect emigration and positive values reflect immigration).  Because global emigration and immigration must balance, changes in this value for a single country/region may not change migration/population as substantially as the change introduced in migrater.

NAME: migrateoutadd
SCENARIO NAME: Migration rate outward additve factor
DEFINITION: Migration rate outward additive factor
Parameter Explanation: Inward migration of a population in percent per year.  Because global emigration and immigration must balance, changes in this value for a single country/region may not change migration/population as substantially as the change introduced originally.

NAME: migrateoutm
SCENARIO NAME: Migration rate outward multiplier
DEFINITION: Migration rate outward multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Migration rate multiplier outward.  A multiplier on migration rate , unit-less, by region.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase mortality and lower values decrease it.

NAME: migrateoutr
SCENARIO NAME: Migration rate (outward), percent of population
DEFINITION: Migration rate (outward), percent of population
Parameter Explanation: Outward migration of a population in percent per year.  Because global emigration and immigration must balance, changes in this value for a single country/region may not change migration/population as substantially as the change introduced originally.

NAME: migrater
SCENARIO NAME: Migration rate (inward), net percent of population
DEFINITION: Migration rate (inward), net percent of population
Parameter Explanation: Net migration of a population in percent per year (negative values reflect emigration and positive values reflect immigration).  Because global emigration and immigration must balance, changes in this value for a single country/region may not change migration/population as substantially as the change introduced in migrater.

NAME: migratesw
SCENARIO NAME: Dyadic migration switch
DEFINITION: Dyadic migration switch
Parameter Explanation: Switch to replace migration in our population module using dyadic formulation

NAME: minpcgr
SCENARIO NAME: Minimum Population Growth to limit IGDPR
DEFINITION: Minimum Population Growth to limit IGDPR
Parameter Explanation: This parameters is used to adjust the impact of population of growh on initialization of economic growth (IGDPR), it adds to POPR/100 for the limit of IGDPR

NAME: mortconv
SCENARIO NAME: Mortality, convergence time to expected value
DEFINITION: Mortality, convergence time to expected value
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that determines the convergence time of mortality to its expected value.  Very often initial data values for countries will differ a little or much from values predicted by a cross-sectional relationship.  It is never certain whether such differences involve data errors or factors idiosyncratic to countries.  A paradigmatic assumption of IFs is that, over time, values for such variables will often gradually converge to the values predicted by the function and the initial country-specific "shift" should disappear. A high value such as 10000 will effectively turn off the convergence process altogether, while a low value such as 10 will make it very rapid.

NAME: mortm
SCENARIO NAME: Mortality multiplier
DEFINITION: Mortality multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on mortality or death, by region and type. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase mortality and lower values decrease it.  Users would introduce an epidemic (like AIDS) by substantially increasing the value.  Scientific advance that greatly increased our age spans could be introduced by a value of 0.5 that is normally phased in.

NAME: mprconv
SCENARIO NAME: Materialism/postmaterialism, convergence time  to expected
DEFINITION: Materialism/postmaterialism, convergence time  to expected
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that determines the convergence time of Materialism/postmaterialism to expected valye based on the analytic function. Very often initial data values for countries will differ a little or much from values predicted by a cross-sectional relationship.  It is never certain whether such differences involve data errors or factors idiosyncratic to countries.  A paradigmatic assumption of IFs is that, over time, values for such variables will often gradually converge to the values predicted by the function and the initial country-specific "shift" should disappear. A high value such as 10000 will effectively turn off the convergence process altogether, while a low value such as 10 will make it very rapid.

NAME: neonatmorm
SCENARIO NAME: Neonatal mortality multiplier
DEFINITION: Neonatal mortality rate, multiplier on neonatal deaths per 1,000 live births
Parameter Explanation: Neonatal mortality rate multiplier. Multiplier on NEONATMORM, unitless, by region. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase NEONATMORM (up to 90% of INFMORM) and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial.

NAME: nmilf
SCENARIO NAME: Nuclear force military spending, portion of total spending
DEFINITION: Nuclear force military spending, portion of total spending
Parameter Explanation: Nuclear military expenditure factor.  A coefficient determining what portion of a country's or region's military expenditure is devoted to nuclear weapons, including delivery systems.  For instance, 0.1 would result in 10 percent.  This can be changed over time and could be used to convert a traditionally nuclear-free region into a nuclear power.  Normal values will range from 0 to 0.2.

NAME: npowf
SCENARIO NAME: Nuclear power factor, warheads/billion $ expenditure
DEFINITION: Nuclear power factor, warheads/billion $ expenditure
DISPLAY UNITS: Warheads per Billion Dollars in Expenditures
Parameter Explanation: Nuclear power factor, warheads/billion $ expenditure.

NAME: nsdiv
SCENARIO NAME: North-South dividing line, GDP per capita
DEFINITION: North-South dividing line, GDP per capita
Parameter Explanation: North-South dividing line, GDP per capita.  This parameter is only used in computing summary measures of the north-south gap in absolute or relative terms.

NAME: nsnaratm
SCENARIO NAME: National survey to national account consumption mean ratio multiplier
DEFINITION: National survey to national account consumption mean ratio multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Mutliplier on the ratio of the mean consumption in survey and national accounts approaches to their calculation.  The ratio is calculated the first year, and changes in the multiplier from 1 allow the user to posit increases or deceases.This parameter only affects the old INCOMELT125LN2005 and INCOMELT200LN2005.

NAME: numnwpgrm
SCENARIO NAME: Number of networked persons, growth rate multiplier
DEFINITION: Number of networked persons, growth rate multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on growth rate of number of networked persons. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase investment and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: nwarf
SCENARIO NAME: Nuclear war, liklihood of conventional war escalation
DEFINITION: Nuclear war, liklihood of conventional war escalation
Parameter Explanation: Nuclear war factor.  This is a reactivity parameter that relates the severity of a conventional war to the probability that nuclear war will erupt between acting and reacting alliances.  A value of 0 eliminates the possibility of nuclear war; a value of 1 creates a probability of war equal to the severity of conventional war (see cwarf).  By setting the value equal to 100 or more you can force the model to generate a war whenever a conventional war erupts.

NAME: nwarsv
SCENARIO NAME: Nuclear war severity, portion of weapons used
DEFINITION: Nuclear war severity, portion of weapons used
Parameter Explanation: Nuclear war severity factor.  This coefficient determines what portion of the nuclear armament potential will be used when a war erupts.  Values should range from 0 (none) to 1 (all).

NAME: oilpcthresw
DISPLAY NAME: Oil Per Capita to Polyrachy Switch
SCENARIO NAME: Oil Per Capita to Polyrachy Switch
DEFINITION: Oil Per Capita to Polyrachy Switch
Parameter Explanation: 0 disables link between oil income per capita and democracy as represented as polyarchy.

NAME: povagesexnormstatic
SCENARIO NAME: Poverty Switch for Normalizing Age-Sex Rates with a Constant Value (1=On, 0=Off)
DEFINITION: Poverty Switch for Normalizing Age-Sex Rates with a Constant Value (1=On, 0=Off)
Parameter Explanation: Switch for normalization of the poverty profile. A value of 0 (as in the base case) will normalize age-sex poverty rates with the national poverty rate forecast. A value of 1 will normalize  age-sex poverty rates using a constant national poverty rate, for example, the base year rate.

NAME: povnational
SCENARIO NAME: National Poverty Line 2011PPP$/Day/Person
DEFINITION: Poverty, national poverty line, income threshold per person per day, 2011 PPP$

NAME: prdthreshold
DISPLAY NAME: Threshold for dyads to be considered relevant per Loss of Strength Gradient
SCENARIO NAME: prdthreshold
DEFINITION: Threshold for dyads to be considered relevant per Loss of Strength Gradient
Parameter Explanation: Used to adjust the value of the threshold used for determining political relevance for THREAT.

NAME: qeunconm
SCENARIO NAME: Q (capital costs-to-output ratio) in unconventional energy, multiplier
DEFINITION: Q (capital costs-to-output ratio) in unconventional energy, multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Capital output ratio for unconventional energy multiplier.  A multiplier on all types of energy capital output, unit-less, by region.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the amount of capital required per unit of energy output and lower values decrease it. Lower this parameter gradually over time to simulate a decreased cost of an energy form (such as renewable energy) as a result of technological advance.  Raise it over time to simulate the addition to the capital cost of an energy form (say nuclear) as a result of the addition to those costs of environmental ones.

NAME: qevremul
SCENARIO NAME: Energy VRE cost increase above VRE share theshold
DEFINITION: Energy, VRE cost increase multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier to impact the VRE cost increase as VRE share goes above threshold. A value of 1 means no impact. Values above 1 means cost increase. Values below 1 means decrease.

NAME: qevrethr
SCENARIO NAME: Energy, VRE share at which system integration starts to impact VRE cost
DEFINITION: Energy, variable renewable energy share at which system integration impact wind and solar cost
Parameter Explanation: A parameter to set the percentage share of VRE in total energy use at which VRE costs (QE) starts to increase.

NAME: randdexpm
SCENARIO NAME: R&D (total) expenditure multiplier
DEFINITION: R&D (total) expenditure multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on R&D expenditure.   A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase the underlying value and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: reac
SCENARIO NAME: Reactivity of countries to threat from each other, military spending
DEFINITION: Reactivity of countries to threat from each other, military spending
Parameter Explanation: Reactivity (Actor, Target).  This parameter determines the magnitude of the threat felt by a target in response to changing power balances with respect to an actor.  A value of 1.5 means that the perceived threat shifts 50 percent faster than the power balance, while a value of .5 means that threat rises only 50 percent as fast.  The user should be aware, however, that in the calculation of how threat affects defense spending, reactivities to ALL actors will shape a country's/region's expenditures, thus often diffusing sensitivity to changes in power of only a single external actor.  By setting reac for all actors towards a target to 0.0, then focusing the attention of a target on a single actor (e.g. reac(Russia, China) = 1.0), you can eliminate that diffusion of attention.

NAME: renewtoenexsw
DISPLAY NAME: Renewable Energy Reduction In Exports Switch
SCENARIO NAME: Renewable Energy Reduction In Exports Switch
DEFINITION: Renewable Energy Reduction In Exports Switch

NAME: resor
SCENARIO NAME: Resources of fossil fuels, ultimate, BBL
DEFINITION: Resources of fossil fuels, ultimate,
Parameter Explanation: Resources of fossil fuels, ultimate, billion barrels of oil equivalent.  This value only sets an initial condition; thereafter resources are computed taking into account depletion from production.

NAME: resorm
SCENARIO NAME: Resources of energy (fossil fuels), multiplier
DEFINITION: Resources of energy (fossil fuels), multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Ultimately recoverable resource multiplier, by energy type.  This parameter allows the user to increase or decrease ultimately recoverable resource values.  A value of 1 accepts the values of RESOR as specified.  A value of 1.5 would raise the resource levels for a specific energy form in a specific country/region by 50 percent.  This multiplier is unusual in that it is only important in the first year - it should not be changed over time because after ultimate resources are calculated the first year they can only run down (be used up).

NAME: resoruncon
SCENARIO NAME: Resources of unconventional fossil fuels, ultimate, BBL
DEFINITION: Resources of unconventional fossil fuels, ultimate,
Parameter Explanation: Resources of unconventional fossil fuels, ultimate, billion barrels of oil equivalent.  This value only sets an initial condition; thereafter resources are computed taking into account depletion from production.

NAME: resorunconm
SCENARIO NAME: Resources of unconventional energy (fossil fuels), multiplier
DEFINITION: Resources of unconventional energy (fossil fuels), multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Ultimately recoverable unconventional resource multiplier, by energy type.  This parameter allows the user to increase or decrease ultimately recoverable resource values.  A value of 1 accepts the values of RESOR as specified.  A value of 1.5 would raise the resource levels for a specific energy form in a specific country/region by 50 percent.  This multiplier is unusual in that it is only important in the first year - it should not be changed over time because after ultimate resources are calculated the first year they can only run down (be used up).

NAME: retireconsumrat
SCENARIO NAME: Ratio of consumption between retirees and all ages
DEFINITION: Ratio of consumption between retirees and all ages
Parameter Explanation: Allows the user to control the spending in retirement relative to average spending at all ages.

NAME: salpha
SCENARIO NAME: Sectorally-specific alpha in value added (capital's share)
DEFINITION: Sectorally-specific alpha in value added (capital's share)
Parameter Explanation: Sectorally-specific alpha in capital's share of value added.  This value has a general empirical base and users will not normally change it.

NAME: samadmissionadd
DISPLAY NAME: SAMs (%) admitted for treatment additive factor
SCENARIO NAME: SAMs (%) admitted for treatment additive factor
DEFINITION: SAMs (%) admitted for treatment additive factor
Parameter Explanation: Additive factor for percentage of SAM cases admitted for treatment.

NAME: samadmissioncost
SCENARIO NAME: Cost per SAM Admission
DEFINITION: Cost per SAM Admission
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that specifies the cost per SAM admission.

NAME: samadmissionm
SCENARIO NAME: SAMs (%) admitted for treatment multiplier
DEFINITION: SAMs (%) admitted for treatment multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on percentage of SAM cases admitted for treatment. A value of 1 represents no change, 1.25 represents a 25 percent increase and .75 represents a 25 percent decrease.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: samadmissionsw
SCENARIO NAME: SAMs (%) admitted for treatment switch
DEFINITION: SAMs (%) admitted for treatment switch (0 is regular forecast, 1 keeps 0s constant, 2 keeps all constant)
Parameter Explanation: Switch for percentage of SAM cases admitted for treatment. A value of 0 shows regular forecast, 1 keeps zeroes constant and a value of 2 keep all constant.

NAME: samavertedconvyr
SCENARIO NAME: SAMs Averted Convergence Years
DEFINITION: SAMs Averted Convergence Years
Parameter Explanation: Convergence time for averted SAM cases.

NAME: samavertedm
SCENARIO NAME: SAMs (%) successfully treated multiplier
DEFINITION: SAMs (%) successfully treated multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Mutliplier on the percentage of SAM cases successfully treated. A value of 1 represents no change, 1.25 represents a 25 percent increase and .75 represents a 25 percent decrease.  Like other multipliers, user should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: samtomalnchpsw
DISPLAY NAME: SAM to Malnutrition switch (when on = 1, averted stay malnourished)
SCENARIO NAME: SAM to Malnutrition switch (when on = 1, averted stay malnourished)
DEFINITION: SAM to Malnutrition switch (when on = 1, averted stay malnourished instead of fully healthy)
Parameter Explanation: Switch to activate linkage between SAM and Malnutrition. A value of 1 indicates on, setting averted SAM cases to malnourished (instead of fully healthy).

NAME: sanitationcostlower
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation connection cost, lower bound
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, Sanitation connection cost, global lower bound

NAME: sanitationcostm
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation, multiplier on cost of adding improved sanitation
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, Sanitation, multiplier on cost of adding improved sanitation facilities to a household

NAME: sanitationcostupper
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation connection cost, upper bound
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, Sanitation connection cost, global upper bound

NAME: sanitationimpcostlower
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation, OtherImproved, Cost  Lower Bound
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, Sanitation, OtherImproved cost, global lower bound

NAME: sanitationimpcostm
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation, OtherImproved, Cost multiplier
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, Sanitation, multiplier on cost of adding other improve sources, per person
Parameter Explanation: Parameter to change the unit cost relative to the base case.

NAME: sanitationimpcostupper
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation, OtherImproved, Cost upper bound
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, Sanitation, OtherImproved cost, global upper bound

NAME: sanitationimplife
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation, other improved, lifetime
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, Sanitation, other improved, lifetime

NAME: sanitationlife
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation, improve sanitation, lifetime
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, Sanitation, improve sanitation, lifetime

NAME: sanitationtrgtval
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation Access Fixed Target Value
DEFINITION: Sanitation Access Target, value for fixed target, percent with hh connection, works with sanitationtrgtyr
Parameter Explanation: Parameter for the  value of percentage with household connections considered as universal access to sanitation.

NAME: sanitationtrgtyr
SCENARIO NAME: Universal Sanitation Access Target Year
DEFINITION: Universal Sanitation Access Target Year (number of years from starting point)
Parameter Explanation: Parameter for the number of years taken to achieve universal access to sanitation (throughhousehold connection)

NAME: sanithhcostlowershr
DISPLAY NAME: Sanitation Services, Share of Services Using Lower-Cost Technology
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation Services, Share of Services Using Lower-Cost Service
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, Sanitation services, share of services using lower-cost service
Parameter Explanation: Infrastructure, Sanitation services, share of services using lower-cost service. Base case value is 50/50 when both lower and upper cost services are available

NAME: sanithldsw
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation hold switch
DEFINITION: Sanitation hold switch
Parameter Explanation: Switch to hold the forecast of Sanitation at Base year levels

NAME: sanitnoconsetar
DISPLAY NAME: Sanitation, No Connection, Standard Error Target
SCENARIO NAME: Sanitation, No Connection, Standard Error Target
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, sanitation, no connection, strandard error target
Parameter Explanation: Sets the number of Standard Errors to be targeted by the forecast (between -2 and 2), 0 turns off the targetting.

NAME: sanitnoconseyrtar
DISPLAY NAME: Years to Target Sanitation, no con, Std Error
SCENARIO NAME: Years to Target Sanitation, no con, Std Error
DEFINITION: Infrastructure, sanitation, no connection, years to target standard error
Parameter Explanation: Sets the number of years to target a given number of Standard Errors by the forecast.

NAME: savingsdiscountrt
SCENARIO NAME: Savings discount rate
DEFINITION: Savings discount rate
Parameter Explanation: Discount rate used to compute working age  and savings rate needed with changes in Life Expectancy.

NAME: sfcivilwarucdpsw
SCENARIO NAME: State failure/internal war UCDEP switch (1 is on)
DEFINITION: State failure/internal war UCDEP switch (1 is on)
Parameter Explanation: State failure/internal war UCDP switch .   When the swithc is 1 the variable SFCIVILWARUCDP will be connected to forward linkagess and parameters, otherwise variable SFINTLWARALL will be used.

NAME: sfconv
SCENARIO NAME: State failure, convergence time to expected value
DEFINITION: State failure, convergence time to expected value
Parameter Explanation: Parameter that determines the convergence time of state failure to its expected value. Very often initial data values for countries will differ a little or much from values predicted by a cross-sectional relationship.  It is never certain whether such differences involve data errors or factors idiosyncratic to countries.  A paradigmatic assumption of IFs is that, over time, values for such variables will often gradually converge to the values predicted by the function and the initial country-specific "shift" should disappear. A high value such as 10000 will effectively turn off the convergence process altogether, while a low value such as 10 will make it very rapid.

NAME: sfintlwaradd
SCENARIO NAME: State failure/internal war, addition
DEFINITION: State failure/internal war, addition
Parameter Explanation: Additive factor to state failure/internal war measure. It introduces a shift in the  probability of internal conflict over time for a region/country.

NAME: sfintlwaralltoginidom
SCENARIO NAME: Conflict to Gini multiplier
DEFINITION: Conflict to Gini multiplier (Base equals 1)
Parameter Explanation: This parameter serves as a multiplier that adjusts the Gini coefficient based on the probability of conflict. It amplifies the Gini index by the set multiplier amount in response to the likelihood of conflict. For example, a multiplier of 1.02 typically suggests a 2% increase in the Gini coefficient. However, the actual increase is adjusted by the probability of conflict; thus, with a 50% probability of conflict, the Gini coefficient would only increase by 1%.

NAME: sfintlwarmagm
SCENARIO NAME: State failure/internal war magnitude, multiplier
DEFINITION: State failure/internal war magnitude, multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on state failure due to instability/internal war. This is a multiplicative factor that introduces a shift in the magnitude of internal conflict over time, for a country/region. It increases/decreases the index value (SFINTLWARALL) that the model computes.

NAME: sfmassrep
SCENARIO NAME: State failure switch/multiplier (>0.05=On), internal war repression by govt
DEFINITION: State failure switch/multiplier (>0.05=On), internal war repression by govt
Parameter Explanation: Switch for state failure mass repression. A value of 1 turns on totalitarian system-like repression that suppresses domestic conflict of any kind and value of 0 represents no such change (default case).

NAME: sfusehist
SCENARIO NAME: State failure, switch to use history for base values (0=off; 1=on; 2=converge)
DEFINITION: State failure, switch to use history for base values (0=off; 1=on; 2=converge)
Parameter Explanation: Switch to use history for base values of state failure. A value of 0 indicates off; 1 indicates on and 2 indicates convergence.

NAME: slr
SCENARIO NAME: Slaughter rate, livestock
DEFINITION: Slaughter rate, livestock
Parameter Explanation: Livestock slaughter rate coefficient represents the proportion of herd slaughtered annually. For example, a rate of 0.7 means 70% of the herd is slaughtered each year.

NAME: ssweltaxrm
SCENARIO NAME: Social security and welfare tax rate multipler
DEFINITION: Social security and welfare tax rate multipler
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on government taxes imposed on both households and firms for social security and welfare, expressed without units and by region. A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase taxes and lower values decrease them.

NAME: survseadd
SCENARIO NAME: Survival/self-expression values, index addition
DEFINITION: Survival/self-expression index addition
Parameter Explanation: Additive factor to introduce a shift in Survival/self-expression index for a region/country.  It increases or decreases the index value that the model calculates.  The normal value is zero.  See also and contrast with cultshmp, which is a cultural shift for the large cultural regions identified in the WVS project and which is calculated from data.

NAME: svdthsadd
DISPLAY NAME: Additive factor on societal violence deaths
SCENARIO NAME: Additive factor on societal violence deaths
DEFINITION: Additive factor on societal violence deaths
Parameter Explanation: Additive factor on societal violence deaths.

NAME: svindexm
DISPLAY NAME: Societal violence index (Self harm multiplier for each component )
SCENARIO NAME: Societal violence index (Self harm multiplier for each component )
DEFINITION: Societal violence index (Self harm multiplier)
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on societal violence index from self-harm.

NAME: svmulm
SCENARIO NAME: Societal violence multiplier
DEFINITION: Societal violence multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on societal violence.

NAME: svtohlsw
DISPLAY NAME: Societal Violence to Health Switch (1 is on)
SCENARIO NAME: Societal Violence to Health Switch (1 is on)
DEFINITION: Societal Violence to Health Switch (1 is on)
Parameter Explanation: Switch to activate linkage between societal violence and health. A value of 1 indicates on; 0 indicates off.

NAME: svvionormsw
DISPLAY NAME: Societal Violence normalization switch (1 is on)
SCENARIO NAME: Societal Violence normalization switch (1 is on)
DEFINITION: Societal Violence normalization switch (1 is on)
Parameter Explanation: Switch for societal violence normalization. A value of 1 indicates on; 0 indicates off.

NAME: swseffects
SCENARIO NAME: Swing State effects switch (1=On, 0=Off)
DEFINITION: Swing State effects switch (1=On, 0=Off)
Parameter Explanation: Action-reaction switch.  A value of 1 (as in the base case) turns on an action-reaction dynamic in the determination of threat.  A value of 0 turns it off.

NAME: swseffmax
SCENARIO NAME: Swing State effects maximum annual magnitude (Polity points)
DEFINITION: Swing State effects maximum annual magnitude (Polity points)
Parameter Explanation: Swing State effects maximum annual magnitude (Polity points).  Because the Polity democracy scale runs from 1-10 (10=most democratic), you would normally not set a value for this parameter of more than 2-4 points, and most often it would be considerably lower.

NAME: taxinfadjm
SCENARIO NAME: Taxrate adjustment from informal economy multiplier
DEFINITION: Taxrate adjustment from informal economy multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on tax rate adjustments because of the extent of informal economy. A value of 0 specifies no adjustment; while a value of 1 specifies full adjustment.

NAME: tconr
SCENARIO NAME: Time-related contraception use increase
DEFINITION: Time-related increase in contraception use
Parameter Explanation: This parameter specifies the increase in time-related contraception use, expressed in percentage terms.

NAME: tefinfadjm
SCENARIO NAME: Productivity adjustment from informal economy multiplier
DEFINITION: Productivity adjustment from informal economy multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on the adjustment of productivity (TEF) because of the extent of informal economy. A value of 0 indicates no adjustment and a value of 1 indicates full adjustment.

NAME: terdispute
SCENARIO NAME: Territorial dispute or absence (1=dispute)
DEFINITION: Territorial dispute or absence (1=dispute)
Parameter Explanation: Territorial dispute or absence (1=dispute; 0=no dispute).  This is a dyadic value, between two countries or regions.  The user could change it from 1 to 0 at some point in time to indicate the resolution of dispute.  The initial values reflect actual disputes in the early 21st century.

NAME: termtrm
SCENARIO NAME: Terms of trade multiplier (higher is better for South)
DEFINITION: Terms of trade multiplier (higher is better for South)
Parameter Explanation: Multiplier on terms of trade.  The default value of this parameter is 1.0, signifying no exogenous shift in the terms of trade between more and less economically developed countries.  Relative prices in various sectors, particularly agriculture and energy, will still change endogenously.  A value greater than 1.0 additionally improves terms of trade for LDCs at the expense of developed countries.  A value of less than 1.0 shifts terms of trade to the benefit of wealthier countries.  A value of 1.2 would improve the terms of trade of the very least developed countries by about 20 percent.  This parameter should not normally be changed from 1 in the initial year.  Values should generally range from .5 to 1.5.

NAME: tfpshockadjshr
DISPLAY NAME: Proportion of GDP shock that has residual impact on TFP/MFP
SCENARIO NAME: Proportion of GDP shock that has residual impact on TFP/MFP
DEFINITION: Proportion of GDP shock that has residual impact on TFP/MFP (rest is capacity adjustment)
Parameter Explanation: In economic shock such as COVID period, the proportion of change to GDP that has persistent impact on TFP (TEFF); rest of affect goes to temporary capacity utilization.

NAME: tfrconv
SCENARIO NAME: TFR (total fertility rate) convergence time to expected value
DEFINITION: TFR (total fertility rate) convergence time to expected value
Parameter Explanation: TFR (total fertility rate) convergence time to expected value.  Very often initial data values for countries will differ a little or much from values predicted by a cross-sectional relationship.  It is never certain whether such differences involve data errors or factors idiosyncratic to countries.  A paradigmatic assumption of IFs is that, over time, values for such variables will often gradually converge to the values predicted by the function and the initial country-specific "shift" should disappear. A high value such as 10000 will effectively turn off the convergence process altogether, while a low value such as 10 will make it very rapid.

NAME: tfrexovals
DISPLAY NAME: Total Fertility Rate Exogenous Values (-100 is off)
SCENARIO NAME: Total Fertility Rate Exogenous Values (-100 is off)
DEFINITION: Total Fertility Rate Exogenous Values (-100 is off)
Parameter Explanation: Total Fertility Rate Exogenous Values (-100 is off)

NAME: tfrm
SCENARIO NAME: TFR (total fertility rate) multiplier
DEFINITION: TFR (total fertility rate) multiplier
Parameter Explanation: Total Fertility Rate multiplier.  A multiplier on TFR, unitless, by region.  A value of 1 implies no change, while higher values proportionately increase TFR (and ultimately increase population) and lower values decrease it.  Like other multipliers, you should generally not change the value in the initial year because that would override empirical initial conditions; rather you should ramp up or down the multiplier value over time.

NAME: tfrmin
SCENARIO NAME: TFR (total fertility rate) stabilization level with high income
DEFINITION: TFR (total fertility rate) stabilization level with high income
Parameter Explanation: TFR (total fertility rate) stabilization level with high income.  This is a very important parameter, because fertility rates in many developed countries have falled well below the 2.1 replacement level.  The level at which they stabilize for countries at the highest levels of income, and when they stabilize (you might change this over time), will greatly effect ultimate global population maximums and possible decline rates.

NAME: tgrld
SCENARIO NAME: Target growth in cultivated land
DEFINITION: Target growth in cultivated land
Parameter Explanation: Target annual growth rate in cultivated land, by region represents the desired annual growth rates for expanding cultivated land.  It is used for computation only in the initial year; thereafter the investment pattern changes endogenously in response to changing agricultural prices and costs.

NAME: threatconstsw
DISPLAY NAME: Switch to hold driver values constant in bilateral THREAT forecasts
SCENARIO NAME: Switch to hold driver values constant in bilateral THREAT forecasts
DEFINITION: Switch to enable constant as inital year values for drivers to be selectively enabled.
Parameter Explanation: Switch used to select mode (0) all variables active, (1) constant trade share, (2)....

NAME: threattradesw
DISPLAY NAME: Used alongside threatconstsw to handle which trade sectors are held constant. 0 uses in-year values for all sectors, 1 keeps all sectors as a %GDP constant for THREAT calculations, and 2 does the same for all sectors.
SCENARIO NAME: Used alongside threatconstsw to handle which trade sectors are held constant.
